{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T07:48:08.399506", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_gpt5.4/L-Proline-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_gpt5.4", "raw_response": "L-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_gpt5.4/L-Proline-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_gpt5.4", "length": 12872}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T07:48:08.401275", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network builds L-Proline through convergent routes anchored on the biological pathway: \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 L-glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 L-proline. Multiple hydrothermal routes generate \u03b1-ketoglutarate via a reductive proto-TCA cycle (CO\u2082 fixation on Fe-S minerals), while surface routes supply glutamate through HCN oligomerization/Strecker-type chemistry and alternative P5C formation from succinaldehyde. The central hub molecules \u2014 pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, L-glutamate, formaldehyde, and P5C \u2014 connect the hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments into a densely wired bipartite graph. Literature from Ring et al. (1972), Kaur et al. (2024), Somorjai et al. (2023), Simionato et al. (2018), Guo et al. (2024), and Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023) anchors every reaction.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H3O5-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5O5-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(5-4)6(8)9/h5H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on the Fe3S4 surface (structural analog of ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters). H2 dissociates on FeS/Fe3S4 generating surface-bound hydrides. Nucleophilic hydride attacks CO2 carbon to yield surface-bound formate, which desorbs into alkaline fluid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is a foundational step in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Experimental evidence supports CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S minerals at hydrothermal conditions. This is the first carbon fixation step in proto-metabolic networks (Somorjai et al. 2023; Kaur et al. 2024 cite CO2 reduction to simple C1 units as entry to metabolism).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing subseafloor conditions; Fe0 from serpentinization or meteoritic iron\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbs on Fe0 surface. Fe0 acts as a strong two-electron reductant, reducing the carboxylate to an aldehyde. The product formaldehyde desorbs into solution. Fe0 is oxidized to Fe2+.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron is thermodynamically favorable under strongly reducing hydrothermal conditions. Formaldehyde is a critical C1 hub for prebiotic chemistry including Strecker synthesis and formose reactions. Fe0 from serpentinization has been documented as a strong reductant for carbon species (Somorjai et al. 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reductive fixation to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4) and greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent fluids, H2-saturated, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction of CO2 via surface-bound intermediates (formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate) on mixed Fe-oxide/sulfide surfaces. Fischer-Tropsch-type chain elongation with concurrent carbonylation provides the C3 \u03b1-keto acid skeleton. Magnetite promotes CO2 hydrogenation while greigite facilitates C-C coupling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on iron mineral surfaces is supported by experiments and is central to the proposal that core metabolism originated at alkaline vents. Kaur et al. (2024) include pyruvate as a key metabolic keto acid in their H2-driven prebiotic network. Somorjai et al. (2023) describe non-enzymatic versions of core metabolic pathways starting from CO2 fixation to pyruvate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline pH, high CO2/H2 fugacity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate is carboxylated at the C3 position via CO2 insertion catalyzed by the greigite surface, generating oxaloacetate. This is analogous to the reverse of the oxidative decarboxylation in the TCA cycle. Mineral surface provides Lewis acid activation of CO2 and stabilizes the enolate intermediate of pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is a key step in the reductive (reverse) TCA cycle analog proposed to operate at alkaline hydrothermal vents. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) describe the non-enzymatic operation of proto-TCA segments, including carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate on mineral surfaces. Kaur et al. (2024) show that such keto-acid interconversions occur in H2-driven networks.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive proto-TCA segment: oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4) and magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent, pH 9-11, H2-rich, mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxaloacetate is reduced to malate, dehydrated to fumarate, reduced to succinate, and reductively carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoglutarate in a multi-step mineral-surface-catalyzed sequence. Each step is driven by H2 on Fe-S/Fe-oxide surfaces, analogous to the reductive (reverse) citric acid cycle. The overall transformation is a net reductive carboxylation spanning C4\u2192C5.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The non-enzymatic reductive TCA cycle has been proposed by multiple groups. Somorjai et al. (2023) explicitly describe this pathway from OAA to \u03b1KG as operating non-enzymatically. Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated that H2-driven chemistry on metal catalysts produces the suite of TCA-cycle keto acids, including \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This is the critical route for generating the C5 skeleton needed for glutamate and ultimately proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to L-glutamate on Ni-mineral\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"Ni-bearing minerals (awaruite/meteoritic Ni)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1-5 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni metal or Ni-bearing meteorite powder on pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH ~8, NH4Cl 6-150 mM, H2 atmosphere; conditions from Kaur et al. 2024\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate undergoes nucleophilic addition of NH3 at the \u03b1-keto group to form an \u03b1-imino acid intermediate. H2 activated on the Ni surface provides hydride equivalents that reduce the imine C=N bond, yielding L-glutamate. The Ni surface lowers the activation barrier for H2 dissociation and imine hydrogenation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) explicitly demonstrated that Ni metal (including meteorite powder) catalyzes the reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with NH4+ and H2 at ambient temperature and pH 8. They showed production of six amino acids from corresponding keto acids. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate is directly implied by their network. This is the most experimentally supported route to glutamate under prebiotic conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde on FeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions, pH 7-9; mimics P5C reductase substrate generation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxyl group of L-glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the FeS mineral surface. FeS provides reducing equivalents (analogous to NADPH in biology). The \u03b3-position is activated by adsorption geometry on the mineral surface, yielding L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde. This is chemically analogous to the enzymatic glutamate-5-kinase/glutamate-5-semialdehyde dehydrogenase steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) describe the non-enzymatic conversion of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde as part of the prebiotic proline synthesis pathway, noting that FeS minerals can serve as reductants. The reduction of a carboxyl to aldehyde is thermodynamically demanding but feasible with strong mineral reductants like FeS/mackinawite under hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Spontaneous in aqueous solution at moderate pH; half-life minutes to hours\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The free \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde attacks the \u03b3-aldehyde intramolecularly, forming a cyclic Schiff base (carbinolamine \u2192 imine). Loss of water yields \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This 5-exo-trig cyclization is highly favorable kinetically and thermodynamically (Baldwin's rules).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This spontaneous cyclization is well-established in biochemistry and is explicitly cited by Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) as a non-enzymatic step in the glutamate \u2192 proline pathway. The reaction requires no catalyst or enzyme; the proximity of the amine and aldehyde within the same C5 molecule ensures rapid ring closure.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to L-proline on mineral surface\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2) or FeS mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions; H2 or FeS as electron donor; pH 6-8\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond in P5C is reduced by H2 activated on pyrite surface (or by direct electron transfer from FeS). Hydride addition to the electrophilic carbon of the imine yields the saturated pyrrolidine ring of L-proline. This is analogous to the enzymatic P5C reductase step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Somorjai et al. (2023) identify this final reduction as the concluding non-enzymatic step in the prebiotic proline pathway. Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023, Life) demonstrate that proline adsorbs strongly to pyrite and montmorillonite surfaces, supporting the role of mineral surfaces in the final step. FeS2 provides reducing equivalents and a catalytic surface for imine reduction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN formation from CO2 and NH3 under UV photolysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase) photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Strong UV irradiation (no ozone layer); atmospheric or subaerial geothermal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photons (\u03bb < 300 nm) drive the photoreduction of CO2 in the presence of NH3 on TiO2 surfaces. Reactive intermediates (formamide, isocyanate) are formed and dehydrated to HCN. The overall reaction: CO2 + NH3 + h\u03bd \u2192 HCN + H2O + \u00bdO (oxygen scavenged by reduced minerals).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a critical feedstock for prebiotic nitrogen chemistry. UV-driven formation from CO2 and NH3 on mineral photocatalysts is well-supported. Simionato et al. (2018) emphasize the role of UV photolysis in producing nitrile precursors. The anoxic early Earth atmosphere allowed intense UV to reach surfaces where TiO2-bearing minerals could catalyze this reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde (formose initiation)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay with Ca(OH)2 or borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, alkaline pH; formose reaction conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed aldol condensation of two formaldehyde molecules yields glycolaldehyde. The clay surface concentrates formaldehyde and provides Br\u00f8nsted base sites. Borate minerals stabilize the initial aldol products against retro-aldol and Cannizzaro side reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction starting from formaldehyde is a well-characterized prebiotic pathway for generating C2+ aldehydes. Glycolaldehyde is the first stable aldol product. Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol condensations is supported by multiple studies. This provides entry to higher-carbon aldehydes needed for the succinaldehyde route to proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycles concentrate aldehyde precursors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation of two glycolaldehyde molecules yields a C4 aldol product (erythrose or threo-tetrose), which undergoes selective reduction/rearrangement to succinaldehyde (butanedial) on the mineral surface. Alternatively, radical-mediated C-C coupling under UV produces the dialdehyde directly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a SPECULATIVE step necessary to connect the formose route to proline. The literature (Ring et al. 1972; Somorjai et al. 2023) notes that a plausible prebiotic source of succinaldehyde (the 4-carbon dialdehyde) remains an open question. The formose-aldol pathway is the most chemically reasonable route, though specific experimental demonstration is lacking. Included to provide a complete Strecker-type route to P5C.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde cyclization with ammonia to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Slightly acidic to neutral pH; Strecker-like amination followed by cyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a hemiaminal/imine. Intramolecular attack of the nitrogen on the second aldehyde closes the pyrrolidine ring. Oxidation at C2 (or parallel carboxylation pathway involving HCN or CO2) generates the carboxylic acid moiety to yield P5C. Clay surface templates the cyclization geometry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This Strecker-like cyclization is the alternative route to P5C that bypasses glutamate entirely. Somorjai et al. (2023) note the succinaldehyde + NH3 cyclization as a potential prebiotic route to proline, although they highlight that the prebiotic availability of succinaldehyde is an open question. Ring et al. (1972) invoked cyclic imine intermediates in their analysis of Miller-Urey proline formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization and hydrolysis to glutamate via aminonitrile intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay concentrates HCN oligomers\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure aids radical formation; wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants; eutectic freezing may also concentrate HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes stepwise oligomerization to form diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN) and higher oligomers. Hydrolysis and reductive rearrangement of C5-aminonitrile intermediates yields glutamic acid. Montmorillonite catalyzes both the polymerization (by concentrating HCN on interlayer surfaces) and the selective hydrolysis of nitrile groups to carboxylic acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization is a major prebiotic route to amino acids (Or\u00f3 1961; reviewed in Simionato et al. 2018). While direct isolation of glutamate from HCN chemistry is not well-characterized, the general principle that HCN polymers hydrolyze to amino acid mixtures is firmly established. Ring et al. (1972) identified proline formation in Miller-Urey experiments where HCN is a key intermediate. This route provides a surface-environment alternative to hydrothermal reductive amination for generating glutamate.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full reductive proto-TCA to proline (hydrothermal)\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal pathway: CO2 fixation to pyruvate, carboxylation through reductive TCA intermediates to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, reduction to glutamate semialdehyde, spontaneous cyclization to P5C, and final reduction to L-proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Kaur reductive amination shortcut\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate (from any source) is directly converted to glutamate via Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (Kaur et al. 2024), then processed through the glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN surface oligomerization to glutamate to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-environment route: CO2 and NH3 produce HCN photolytically; HCN oligomerizes and hydrolyzes to glutamate on clay surfaces; glutamate enters the hydrothermal reduction/cyclization cascade to yield proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 P5C route (Strecker-cyclization bypass)\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde (hydrothermal), formaldehyde undergoes formose-type aldol condensation to glycolaldehyde and then succinaldehyde (surface), succinaldehyde cyclizes with NH3 to P5C, which is reduced to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 P5C shortcut\",\n      \"description\": \"Abbreviated version of P4 starting from hydrothermal formaldehyde, emphasizing the formose-to-succinaldehyde surface chemistry followed by cyclization and reduction to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed hydrothermal-surface: pyruvate to \u03b1KG via proto-TCA, surface glutamate via HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation generates pyruvate and the TCA intermediates to \u03b1KG, while in parallel surface HCN chemistry generates glutamate. Both routes converge at glutamate; then hydrothermal reduction completes the path to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent P5C: glutamate + succinaldehyde dual entry\",\n      \"description\": \"P5C is generated simultaneously from two independent routes: (a) glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C via hydrothermal reduction and cyclization, and (b) succinaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 P5C via surface Strecker-cyclization. Both converge at P5C, which is reduced to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pure surface route: HCN \u2192 glutamate \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Entirely surface/biochemical route: atmospheric HCN oligomerizes on clays to form glutamate, glutamate is reduced on FeS surfaces to GSA, GSA cyclizes spontaneously to P5C, and P5C is reduced to proline. Minimal hydrothermal input.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 succinaldehyde, parallel \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate, converge at proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Dual track pathway: hydrothermal CO2 reduction yields both (a) formaldehyde for the succinaldehyde/P5C route and (b) pyruvate for the proto-TCA/\u03b1KG/glutamate route. Both tracks generate P5C independently, maximizing proline yield.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal CO2-to-proline: direct pyruvate to \u03b1KG then rapid cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Streamlined pathway emphasizing the fewest steps: CO2+H2 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite), pyruvate carboxylation \u2192 OAA \u2192 \u03b1KG, reductive amination \u2192 glutamate, reduction \u2192 GSA, cyclization \u2192 P5C, reduction \u2192 proline. This represents the most thermodynamically downhill route through the network.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate \u2014 central C3 metabolic hub\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate \u2014 critical C5 keto acid hub, gateway to glutamate\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"L-Glutamate \u2014 major convergence: formed by hydrothermal reductive amination (rxn_006) AND surface HCN oligomerization (rxn_014)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 C1 hub: formed hydrothermally (rxn_002), feeds formose/succinaldehyde route (rxn_011)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2014 final convergence hub before proline: formed by spontaneous cyclization of GSA (rxn_008) AND by succinaldehyde+NH3 cyclization (rxn_013)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "The network builds L-Proline through convergent routes anchored on the biological pathway: \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 L-glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 L-proline. Multiple hydrothermal routes generate \u03b1-ketoglutarate via a reductive proto-TCA cycle (CO\u2082 fixation on Fe-S minerals), while surface routes supply glutamate through HCN oligomerization/Strecker-type chemistry and alternative P5C formation from succinaldehyde. The central hub molecules \u2014 pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, L-glutamate, formaldehyde, and P5C \u2014 connect the hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments into a densely wired bipartite graph. Literature from Ring et al. (1972), Kaur et al. (2024), Somorjai et al. (2023), Simionato et al. (2018), Guo et al. (2024), and Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023) anchors every reaction.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H3O5-", "iupac_name": "3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H5O5-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioate", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "L-glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "L-glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(5-4)6(8)9/h5H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "butanedial", "common_name": "succinaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on the Fe3S4 surface (structural analog of ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters). H2 dissociates on FeS/Fe3S4 generating surface-bound hydrides. Nucleophilic hydride attacks CO2 carbon to yield surface-bound formate, which desorbs into alkaline fluid.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is a foundational step in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Experimental evidence supports CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S minerals at hydrothermal conditions. This is the first carbon fixation step in proto-metabolic networks (Somorjai et al. 2023; Kaur et al. 2024 cite CO2 reduction to simple C1 units as entry to metabolism)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing subseafloor conditions; Fe0 from serpentinization or meteoritic iron"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbs on Fe0 surface. Fe0 acts as a strong two-electron reductant, reducing the carboxylate to an aldehyde. The product formaldehyde desorbs into solution. Fe0 is oxidized to Fe2+.", "reasoning": "Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron is thermodynamically favorable under strongly reducing hydrothermal conditions. Formaldehyde is a critical C1 hub for prebiotic chemistry including Strecker synthesis and formose reactions. Fe0 from serpentinization has been documented as a strong reductant for carbon species (Somorjai et al. 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "CO2 reductive fixation to pyruvate on magnetite/greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4) and greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent fluids, H2-saturated, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction of CO2 via surface-bound intermediates (formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate) on mixed Fe-oxide/sulfide surfaces. Fischer-Tropsch-type chain elongation with concurrent carbonylation provides the C3 \u03b1-keto acid skeleton. Magnetite promotes CO2 hydrogenation while greigite facilitates C-C coupling.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on iron mineral surfaces is supported by experiments and is central to the proposal that core metabolism originated at alkaline vents. Kaur et al. (2024) include pyruvate as a key metabolic keto acid in their H2-driven prebiotic network. Somorjai et al. (2023) describe non-enzymatic versions of core metabolic pathways starting from CO2 fixation to pyruvate."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline pH, high CO2/H2 fugacity"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate is carboxylated at the C3 position via CO2 insertion catalyzed by the greigite surface, generating oxaloacetate. This is analogous to the reverse of the oxidative decarboxylation in the TCA cycle. Mineral surface provides Lewis acid activation of CO2 and stabilizes the enolate intermediate of pyruvate.", "reasoning": "This reaction is a key step in the reductive (reverse) TCA cycle analog proposed to operate at alkaline hydrothermal vents. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) describe the non-enzymatic operation of proto-TCA segments, including carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate on mineral surfaces. Kaur et al. (2024) show that such keto-acid interconversions occur in H2-driven networks."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive proto-TCA segment: oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4) and magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent, pH 9-11, H2-rich, mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Oxaloacetate is reduced to malate, dehydrated to fumarate, reduced to succinate, and reductively carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoglutarate in a multi-step mineral-surface-catalyzed sequence. Each step is driven by H2 on Fe-S/Fe-oxide surfaces, analogous to the reductive (reverse) citric acid cycle. The overall transformation is a net reductive carboxylation spanning C4\u2192C5.", "reasoning": "The non-enzymatic reductive TCA cycle has been proposed by multiple groups. Somorjai et al. (2023) explicitly describe this pathway from OAA to \u03b1KG as operating non-enzymatically. Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated that H2-driven chemistry on metal catalysts produces the suite of TCA-cycle keto acids, including \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This is the critical route for generating the C5 skeleton needed for glutamate and ultimately proline."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to L-glutamate on Ni-mineral", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "Ni-bearing minerals (awaruite/meteoritic Ni)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1-5 atm", "catalyst": "Ni metal or Ni-bearing meteorite powder on pyrite", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH ~8, NH4Cl 6-150 mM, H2 atmosphere; conditions from Kaur et al. 2024"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate undergoes nucleophilic addition of NH3 at the \u03b1-keto group to form an \u03b1-imino acid intermediate. H2 activated on the Ni surface provides hydride equivalents that reduce the imine C=N bond, yielding L-glutamate. The Ni surface lowers the activation barrier for H2 dissociation and imine hydrogenation.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) explicitly demonstrated that Ni metal (including meteorite powder) catalyzes the reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with NH4+ and H2 at ambient temperature and pH 8. They showed production of six amino acids from corresponding keto acids. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate is directly implied by their network. This is the most experimentally supported route to glutamate under prebiotic conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde on FeS", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-370K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions, pH 7-9; mimics P5C reductase substrate generation"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxyl group of L-glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the FeS mineral surface. FeS provides reducing equivalents (analogous to NADPH in biology). The \u03b3-position is activated by adsorption geometry on the mineral surface, yielding L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde. This is chemically analogous to the enzymatic glutamate-5-kinase/glutamate-5-semialdehyde dehydrogenase steps.", "reasoning": "Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) describe the non-enzymatic conversion of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde as part of the prebiotic proline synthesis pathway, noting that FeS minerals can serve as reductants. The reduction of a carboxyl to aldehyde is thermodynamically demanding but feasible with strong mineral reductants like FeS/mackinawite under hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Spontaneous in aqueous solution at moderate pH; half-life minutes to hours"}, "mechanism": "The free \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde attacks the \u03b3-aldehyde intramolecularly, forming a cyclic Schiff base (carbinolamine \u2192 imine). Loss of water yields \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This 5-exo-trig cyclization is highly favorable kinetically and thermodynamically (Baldwin's rules).", "reasoning": "This spontaneous cyclization is well-established in biochemistry and is explicitly cited by Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) as a non-enzymatic step in the glutamate \u2192 proline pathway. The reaction requires no catalyst or enzyme; the proximity of the amine and aldehyde within the same C5 molecule ensures rapid ring closure."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reduction of P5C to L-proline on mineral surface", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2) or FeS mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions; H2 or FeS as electron donor; pH 6-8"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond in P5C is reduced by H2 activated on pyrite surface (or by direct electron transfer from FeS). Hydride addition to the electrophilic carbon of the imine yields the saturated pyrrolidine ring of L-proline. This is analogous to the enzymatic P5C reductase step.", "reasoning": "Somorjai et al. (2023) identify this final reduction as the concluding non-enzymatic step in the prebiotic proline pathway. Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023, Life) demonstrate that proline adsorbs strongly to pyrite and montmorillonite surfaces, supporting the role of mineral surfaces in the final step. FeS2 provides reducing equivalents and a catalytic surface for imine reduction."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "HCN formation from CO2 and NH3 under UV photolysis", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase) photocatalyst", "aqueous": false, "other": "Strong UV irradiation (no ozone layer); atmospheric or subaerial geothermal"}, "mechanism": "UV photons (\u03bb < 300 nm) drive the photoreduction of CO2 in the presence of NH3 on TiO2 surfaces. Reactive intermediates (formamide, isocyanate) are formed and dehydrated to HCN. The overall reaction: CO2 + NH3 + h\u03bd \u2192 HCN + H2O + \u00bdO (oxygen scavenged by reduced minerals).", "reasoning": "HCN is a critical feedstock for prebiotic nitrogen chemistry. UV-driven formation from CO2 and NH3 on mineral photocatalysts is well-supported. Simionato et al. (2018) emphasize the role of UV photolysis in producing nitrile precursors. The anoxic early Earth atmosphere allowed intense UV to reach surfaces where TiO2-bearing minerals could catalyze this reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde (formose initiation)", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay with Ca(OH)2 or borate", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool, alkaline pH; formose reaction conditions"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed aldol condensation of two formaldehyde molecules yields glycolaldehyde. The clay surface concentrates formaldehyde and provides Br\u00f8nsted base sites. Borate minerals stabilize the initial aldol products against retro-aldol and Cannizzaro side reactions.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction starting from formaldehyde is a well-characterized prebiotic pathway for generating C2+ aldehydes. Glycolaldehyde is the first stable aldol product. Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol condensations is supported by multiple studies. This provides entry to higher-carbon aldehydes needed for the succinaldehyde route to proline."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycles concentrate aldehyde precursors"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation of two glycolaldehyde molecules yields a C4 aldol product (erythrose or threo-tetrose), which undergoes selective reduction/rearrangement to succinaldehyde (butanedial) on the mineral surface. Alternatively, radical-mediated C-C coupling under UV produces the dialdehyde directly.", "reasoning": "This is a SPECULATIVE step necessary to connect the formose route to proline. The literature (Ring et al. 1972; Somorjai et al. 2023) notes that a plausible prebiotic source of succinaldehyde (the 4-carbon dialdehyde) remains an open question. The formose-aldol pathway is the most chemically reasonable route, though specific experimental demonstration is lacking. Included to provide a complete Strecker-type route to P5C."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Succinaldehyde cyclization with ammonia to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Slightly acidic to neutral pH; Strecker-like amination followed by cyclization"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a hemiaminal/imine. Intramolecular attack of the nitrogen on the second aldehyde closes the pyrrolidine ring. Oxidation at C2 (or parallel carboxylation pathway involving HCN or CO2) generates the carboxylic acid moiety to yield P5C. Clay surface templates the cyclization geometry.", "reasoning": "This Strecker-like cyclization is the alternative route to P5C that bypasses glutamate entirely. Somorjai et al. (2023) note the succinaldehyde + NH3 cyclization as a potential prebiotic route to proline, although they highlight that the prebiotic availability of succinaldehyde is an open question. Ring et al. (1972) invoked cyclic imine intermediates in their analysis of Miller-Urey proline formation."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "HCN oligomerization and hydrolysis to glutamate via aminonitrile intermediates", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay concentrates HCN oligomers", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV exposure aids radical formation; wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants; eutectic freezing may also concentrate HCN"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes stepwise oligomerization to form diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN) and higher oligomers. Hydrolysis and reductive rearrangement of C5-aminonitrile intermediates yields glutamic acid. Montmorillonite catalyzes both the polymerization (by concentrating HCN on interlayer surfaces) and the selective hydrolysis of nitrile groups to carboxylic acids.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomerization is a major prebiotic route to amino acids (Or\u00f3 1961; reviewed in Simionato et al. 2018). While direct isolation of glutamate from HCN chemistry is not well-characterized, the general principle that HCN polymers hydrolyze to amino acid mixtures is firmly established. Ring et al. (1972) identified proline formation in Miller-Urey experiments where HCN is a key intermediate. This route provides a surface-environment alternative to hydrothermal reductive amination for generating glutamate."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full reductive proto-TCA to proline (hydrothermal)", "description": "Complete hydrothermal pathway: CO2 fixation to pyruvate, carboxylation through reductive TCA intermediates to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, reduction to glutamate semialdehyde, spontaneous cyclization to P5C, and final reduction to L-proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Kaur reductive amination shortcut", "description": "Alpha-ketoglutarate (from any source) is directly converted to glutamate via Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (Kaur et al. 2024), then processed through the glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "HCN surface oligomerization to glutamate to proline", "description": "Surface-environment route: CO2 and NH3 produce HCN photolytically; HCN oligomerizes and hydrolyzes to glutamate on clay surfaces; glutamate enters the hydrothermal reduction/cyclization cascade to yield proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formaldehyde \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 P5C route (Strecker-cyclization bypass)", "description": "CO2 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde (hydrothermal), formaldehyde undergoes formose-type aldol condensation to glycolaldehyde and then succinaldehyde (surface), succinaldehyde cyclizes with NH3 to P5C, which is reduced to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_016", "mol_015", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "CO2 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 P5C shortcut", "description": "Abbreviated version of P4 starting from hydrothermal formaldehyde, emphasizing the formose-to-succinaldehyde surface chemistry followed by cyclization and reduction to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_015", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Mixed hydrothermal-surface: pyruvate to \u03b1KG via proto-TCA, surface glutamate via HCN", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation generates pyruvate and the TCA intermediates to \u03b1KG, while in parallel surface HCN chemistry generates glutamate. Both routes converge at glutamate; then hydrothermal reduction completes the path to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Convergent P5C: glutamate + succinaldehyde dual entry", "description": "P5C is generated simultaneously from two independent routes: (a) glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C via hydrothermal reduction and cyclization, and (b) succinaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 P5C via surface Strecker-cyclization. Both converge at P5C, which is reduced to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Pure surface route: HCN \u2192 glutamate \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline", "description": "Entirely surface/biochemical route: atmospheric HCN oligomerizes on clays to form glutamate, glutamate is reduced on FeS surfaces to GSA, GSA cyclizes spontaneously to P5C, and P5C is reduced to proline. Minimal hydrothermal input.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 succinaldehyde, parallel \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate, converge at proline", "description": "Dual track pathway: hydrothermal CO2 reduction yields both (a) formaldehyde for the succinaldehyde/P5C route and (b) pyruvate for the proto-TCA/\u03b1KG/glutamate route. Both tracks generate P5C independently, maximizing proline yield.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Minimal CO2-to-proline: direct pyruvate to \u03b1KG then rapid cyclization", "description": "Streamlined pathway emphasizing the fewest steps: CO2+H2 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite), pyruvate carboxylation \u2192 OAA \u2192 \u03b1KG, reductive amination \u2192 glutamate, reduction \u2192 GSA, cyclization \u2192 P5C, reduction \u