b1KG\u2192Glu\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192Pro) while providing alternative entries via succinaldehyde and HCN oligomerization. Literature alignment is good \u2014 the network properly incorporates Kaur et al. (2024) for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination, Somorjai et al. (2023) for proto-TCA logic, and acknowledges Ring et al. (1972) as the only direct proline detection. The convergence at P5C from two independent routes is elegant. However, several critical issues prevent approval: (1) rxn_005 (OAA\u2192\u03b1KG) is an oversimplified lumped reaction hiding 3-4 distinct transformations; (2) rxn_007 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction) is the key unproven step and the literature explicitly flags this as a major open challenge; (3) rxn_012 (glycolaldehyde\u2192succinaldehyde) produces the wrong product class (sugars, not dialdehydes); (4) some hub molecules (pyruvate, \u03b1KG, formaldehyde) have degree \u2264 2, not truly hub-like; (5) the 'L-' stereochemical specificity is never mechanistically justified. The network honestly reflects the state of the field \u2014 as the literature notes, 'no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated' \u2014 but needs specific chemical fixes to cross the approval threshold. The strongest route is the proto-TCA\u2192glutamate\u2192P5C\u2192proline pathway, which should be expanded with explicit intermediates and better-justified reduction chemistry.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.65, "convergence_quality": 0.78}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 295032.69624710083, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T08:03:37.268207", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.73\n- Feedback: This is an ambitious and well-structured synthesis network for L-Proline that demonstrates strong conceptual design. The overall strategy mirrors the biological biosynthetic route (\u03b1KG\u2192Glu\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192Pro) while providing alternative entries via succinaldehyde and HCN oligomerization. Literature alignment is good \u2014 the network properly incorporates Kaur et al. (2024) for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination, Somorjai et al. (2023) for proto-TCA logic, and acknowledges Ring et al. (1972) as the only direct proline detection. The convergence at P5C from two independent routes is elegant. However, several critical issues prevent approval: (1) rxn_005 (OAA\u2192\u03b1KG) is an oversimplified lumped reaction hiding 3-4 distinct transformations; (2) rxn_007 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction) is the key unproven step and the literature explicitly flags this as a major open challenge; (3) rxn_012 (glycolaldehyde\u2192succinaldehyde) produces the wrong product class (sugars, not dialdehydes); (4) some hub molecules (pyruvate, \u03b1KG, formaldehyde) have degree \u2264 2, not truly hub-like; (5) the 'L-' stereochemical specificity is never mechanistically justified. The network honestly reflects the state of the field \u2014 as the literature notes, 'no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated' \u2014 but needs specific chemical fixes to cross the approval threshold. The strongest route is the proto-TCA\u2192glutamate\u2192P5C\u2192proline pathway, which should be expanded with explicit intermediates and better-justified reduction chemistry.\n- Issues: ['The full reductive proto-TCA route is well-motivated and mirrors the biological biosynthetic logic (\u03b1KG\u2192Glu\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192Pro). Key bottleneck is rxn_005 which lumps OAA\u2192\u03b1KG via multiple proto-TCA intermediates (malate, fumarate, succinate) into a single step, masking considerable complexity. rxn_007 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to semialdehyde) is the critical unproven step \u2014 enzymatic specificity is hard to replicate prebiotically on FeS. The spontaneous cyclization (rxn_008) and final reduction (rxn_009) are more plausible.', \"Described as a 'Kaur reductive amination shortcut' but pathway is underspecified. If it bypasses the glutamate\u2192semialdehyde\u2192P5C steps, it's unclear how \u03b1KG+Glu reaches proline without cyclization. Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated glutamate from \u03b1KG on Ni, not proline directly. The shortcut claim needs mechanistic justification for how cyclization occurs in this abbreviated route.\", 'HCN oligomerization to glutamate (rxn_014) is plausible for simple amino acids (glycine, alanine) but producing a 5-carbon amino acid specifically from HCN is low-yield and poorly demonstrated. rxn_010 (CO\u2082+NH\u2083\u2192HCN under UV) is non-standard; traditional HCN sources are CH\u2084+N\u2082 or CO+NH\u2083 under discharge. The surface\u2192biochemical transition is reasonable. Still requires the problematic \u03b3-carboxyl reduction (rxn_007).', \"This route via succinaldehyde directly addresses an alternative P5C formation mechanism. However, rxn_012 is the weakest link: aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde gives C4 sugars (erythrose/threose), not succinaldehyde (a dialdehyde). The literature explicitly notes that succinaldehyde 'has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions.' rxn_013 (succinaldehyde+NH\u2083\u2192P5C) is chemically logical but undemonstrated. This pathway is creative but speculative.\", 'Same core issues as P4 \u2014 the succinaldehyde formation step (rxn_012) is not chemically sound as written. The hydrothermal-to-surface transition (formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192surface formose) is well-conceived but the aldol product selectivity is wrong.', 'Interesting mixed pathway that leverages both environments, but inherits weaknesses from both hydrothermal (rxn_005 lumping) and surface (rxn_010, rxn_014) routes. The convergence concept is sound but each branch has unresolved issues.', 'The dual P5C entry point (from glutamate and from succinaldehyde) is a clever convergent design. However, both branches to P5C have their own weak points: the glutamate branch requires rxn_007, and the succinaldehyde branch requires rxn_012. The convergence at P5C is the strongest aspect.', 'Pure surface route loses the advantage of hydrothermal mineral catalysis. Environmental progression is weak since all steps except the last two are surface, and the Biochemical label for rxn_008/009 is thin. rxn_014 producing glutamate from HCN is speculative for this specific 5-carbon product.', 'This is the most comprehensive convergent pathway, drawing from both formaldehyde and proto-TCA branches. The environmental flow is well-structured (hydrothermal \u2192 surface \u2192 biochemical). However, at 10 steps it inherits all the problematic reactions (rxn_005, rxn_012). The convergence at proline is logically sound despite individual step weaknesses.', \"Essentially the same as P1 but labeled as 'minimal.' This is the most plausible single linear route, anchored by Kaur et al. (2024) for the reductive amination step. The main bottlenecks remain rxn_005 (lumped proto-TCA) and rxn_007 (selective reduction). The 'rapid cyclization' claim for P5C formation is valid (spontaneous). This is tied with P1 as the best pathway.\"]\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network constructs L-proline via the prebiotically plausible biosynthetic analog: CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 proto-TCA cycle intermediates (with each step explicit: oxaloacetate \u2192 malate \u2192 fumarate \u2192 succinate) \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. Two routes to pyruvate (via formate or direct Fe\u2070 reduction), two routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate (full proto-TCA or a reductive carboxylation shortcut from pyruvate), and two routes to glutamate (direct Ni-catalyzed reductive amination or transamination via alanine) create combinatorial branching that yields 10 distinct pathways. The \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to GS-Ald is explicitly flagged as the key unproven bottleneck. Product is racemic DL-proline; L-enrichment may arise from asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023) or downstream selection in peptide systems. Literature anchors: Kaur et al. 2024 for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination, Somorjai et al. 2023 / Phil. Trans. for non-enzymatic glutamate\u2192P5C\u2192proline cyclization, Ring et al. 1972 for experimental proline detection, Guo et al. 2024 for mineral-mediated prebiotic condensation.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia / ammonium\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4-6)1-3(7)8/h1H2,(H,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxybutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"malate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c5-2(4-8)1-3(6)7/h2,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(E)-butenedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"fumarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3-5(8)9/h3-4H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-saturated fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface via Fe-O interactions; H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. Formate is released as the two-electron reduction product of CO\u2082. Greigite's [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-like cubane clusters facilitate this electron transfer, analogous to modern carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase active sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the most well-supported prebiotic reactions. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) is a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters and catalyzes this reduction under hydrothermal conditions. Demonstrated by multiple groups studying prebiotic carbon fixation at alkaline vents (reviewed in Somorjai et al. 2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.). Kaur et al. (2024) also note the importance of formate as a C1 building block in prebiotic networks.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carbonylation of formate to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) / mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mixed mineral surface, alkaline vent fluid, CO\u2082 and H\u2082 in excess\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced to a formyl/carbonyl intermediate on the mineral surface. Sequential C-C bond formation via CO insertion (analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl acetyl-CoA pathway) followed by a second CO\u2082 reduction step yields a C3 \u03b1-keto acid (pyruvate). The mineral surface stabilizes reactive intermediates and promotes reductive C-C coupling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate formation from CO\u2082/formate under hydrothermal conditions on Fe-Ni-S minerals has been demonstrated and represents a prebiotic analog of the acetyl-CoA pathway extended by one carbon. This is consistent with the proto-metabolic network model of Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) and the concept that core metabolic intermediates arose abiotically on mineral surfaces. Magnetite and mackinawite surfaces promote Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C bond formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe\u2070 with magnetite co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Native iron from meteoritic input or serpentinization, strongly reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Elemental iron acts as a strong two-electron reductant, reducing CO\u2082 in multiple sequential steps. Fe\u2070 surface provides both electrons and a catalytic template for C-C bond formation, generating pyruvate as a C3 product via sequential carboxylation and reduction steps without requiring a discrete formate intermediate in solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on Fe\u2070 under hydrothermal conditions has been reported as a plausible prebiotic route. Native iron from meteoritic material or serpentinization provides a strong reductant. This parallels findings where Fe\u2070 promotes multi-carbon product formation from CO\u2082 at moderate hydrothermal temperatures (Somorjai et al. 2023; reviewed in context of proto-TCA cycle analogs). Provides an alternative to the stepwise formate route (rxn_001\u2192rxn_002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluid, mineral surface promotes carboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes carboxylation at the C3 position (analogous to pyruvate carboxylase) on the magnetite surface. The mineral provides Lewis acid sites that activate CO\u2082 and stabilize the oxaloacetate product via surface adsorption, preventing decarboxylation back to pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate is a key step in the reductive TCA cycle and its prebiotic analog. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) discuss this as part of the non-enzymatic proto-metabolic network. Under high CO\u2082 pressure at hydrothermal conditions, the equilibrium favors carboxylation. Mineral surfaces (magnetite, greigite) stabilize the product and lower the activation barrier.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluid, reductive conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The keto group of oxaloacetate is reduced to a hydroxyl group by H\u2082 dissociated on the greigite surface, yielding malate. This is a straightforward two-electron reduction analogous to the malate dehydrogenase step in the rTCA cycle. The Fe-S surface provides hydride equivalents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of \u03b1-keto acids on Fe-S mineral surfaces is well-established. This step mirrors the rTCA cycle (oxaloacetate \u2192 malate) and has been discussed as prebiotically feasible by Somorjai et al. (2023). Greigite's [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-like clusters are effective for carbonyl reduction using H\u2082 as reductant.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Dehydration of malate to fumarate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082) surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Surface-adsorbed malate undergoes elimination; moderate heating at vent temperatures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Malate adsorbs to the pyrite surface via its carboxylate groups. The mineral surface facilitates anti-elimination of water from the C2-C3 bond, generating the trans-alkene fumarate. Elevated temperature and surface activation lower the kinetic barrier for this dehydration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dehydration of malate to fumarate is thermodynamically favorable at elevated temperatures and is a standard step in the rTCA cycle analog. Pyrite surfaces can promote dehydration reactions through surface binding and Lewis acid catalysis (Somorjai et al. 2023). This explicit step was previously lumped with adjacent reactions; it is shown separately here to accurately represent the proto-TCA sequence.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of fumarate to succinate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082-saturated alkaline vent fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=C double bond of fumarate is hydrogenated by H\u2082 on the greigite surface, yielding succinate. The mineral provides dissociative H\u2082 activation, and the two hydrogen atoms add across the double bond in a syn or anti fashion depending on surface geometry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrogenation of fumarate to succinate on Fe-S surfaces is one of the more straightforward prebiotic reactions in the proto-TCA sequence. It is the analog of succinate dehydrogenase (in reverse). Somorjai et al. (2023) include this as part of the non-enzymatic rTCA network. Greigite is an effective hydrogenation catalyst under hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with greigite co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"High CO\u2082 partial pressure drives carboxylation equilibrium; strongly reducing conditions required\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Succinate undergoes oxidative activation at the \u03b1-carbon on the mineral surface, followed by CO\u2082 insertion to form \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Alternatively, succinate is first activated to succinyl-thioester analog on the FeS surface, then carboxylated. This is the most thermodynamically demanding step in the proto-TCA segment and requires both high CO\u2082 pressure and strong reducing conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate is the critical C4\u2192C5 step in the rTCA cycle. This is one of the more challenging steps prebiotically, as noted by Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.). High CO\u2082 pressure and mineral catalysis are required. The reaction has been proposed to occur on mixed Fe-Ni-S mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. This step is explicitly separated from the preceding malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate sequence to avoid the lumping criticized in the prior attempt.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation shortcut: pyruvate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe\u2070 / greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Strongly reducing, CO\u2082 and formate co-substrates, bypasses discrete OAA-malate-fumarate-succinate intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes sequential reductive carboxylation with CO\u2082 and/or carbonylation with formate-derived C1 units on the Fe\u2070 surface. The strong reducing power of native iron drives C-C bond formation through a putative succinyl intermediate that is further carboxylated to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate without accumulating free malate/fumarate/succinate intermediates. This is a surface-confined multi-step process where intermediates remain adsorbed.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This shortcut route represents a surface-confined version of the proto-TCA where intermediates do not desorb into solution. While speculative, it is thermodynamically plausible given the strongly reducing conditions provided by Fe\u2070. The concept of surface-confined multi-step pathways on mineral catalysts is discussed by Somorjai et al. (2023) and is analogous to how modern enzymes confine intermediates. This alternative route addresses the need for pathway diversity and acknowledges that not all intermediates may accumulate as free species. EXPLICITLY LABELED AS SPECULATIVE\u2014no direct experimental demonstration of this specific shortcut exists.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Ni-doped pyrite (FeS\u2082/Ni)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K (22\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm (H\u2082 atmosphere)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni metal or Ni-bearing meteorite material on pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, 6-150 mM NH\u2084Cl, Ni catalyst (from meteorite powder or awaruite), ambient temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate reacts with NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate at the \u03b1-keto position. H\u2082 dissociates on the Ni surface and reduces the C=N bond, yielding glutamate. The Ni catalyst provides the hydrogenation activity essential for driving the equilibrium toward the amino acid product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly supported by Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) who demonstrated that Ni catalyst (including meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl converts biological \u03b1-keto acids to corresponding amino acids. They showed six keto acids including glyoxylate were converted; \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate is explicitly implied by their protometabolic network. This is the strongest experimentally supported step linking hydrothermal keto acids to amino acids. Product is racemic DL-glutamate; L-enrichment is not addressed by this reaction alone.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Ni-doped pyrite (FeS\u2082/Ni)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K (22\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm (H\u2082 atmosphere)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni metal or Ni-bearing meteorite material\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, 6-150 mM NH\u2084Cl, same conditions as rxn_010\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine intermediate at the C2 keto position. Ni-catalyzed H\u2082 reduction of the C=N bond yields alanine. Mechanism is identical to rxn_010 but with the C3 substrate pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) explicitly demonstrated pyruvate \u2192 alanine under these conditions as part of their prebiotic amino acid synthesis network. Alanine is one of the amino acids formed in good yield. Here it serves as an amino group donor for subsequent transamination to glutamate, creating a second route to this key intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination: alanine + \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate + pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface, possibly with trace metal ions (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, pyridoxal or \u03b1-keto acid mediated\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine donates its amino group to \u03b1-ketoglutarate via a pyridoxal-independent transamination. The \u03b1-amino group of alanine attacks the \u03b1-keto carbonyl of \u03b1KG, forming a geminal diamine intermediate that rearranges to transfer the amino group, yielding glutamate and regenerating pyruvate. Clay surfaces catalyze this by co-adsorbing and orienting both substrates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids is well-documented in prebiotic chemistry and occurs readily at moderate temperatures with metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a). This reaction creates a second route to glutamate (from alanine + \u03b1KG) independent of direct reductive amination. Importantly, it also regenerates pyruvate, creating a catalytic cycle. The biological relevance of transamination in early metabolism is discussed by Somorjai et al. (2023) and is central to the concept that amino acid synthesis predated enzymes. Montmorillonite catalysis of amino acid reactions is supported by Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive conversion of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl to semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate (1-10 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS / greigite mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly reducing conditions, pH 7-9; KEY BOTTLENECK: selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction over \u03b1-carboxyl is the critical unresolved challenge\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde by H\u2082 on the FeS surface, yielding glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald). Selectivity for the \u03b3-position may arise from differential adsorption geometry on the mineral surface: the \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxyl groups chelate to Fe sites, leaving the \u03b3-carboxyl exposed for reduction. Alternatively, partial activation via a thioester intermediate (\u03b3-carboxyl + surface sulfide \u2192 thioester \u2192 aldehyde) could provide selectivity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the KEY BOTTLENECK of the entire proline synthesis network, as explicitly acknowledged in the literature. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) describe the glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline sequence as the non-enzymatic analog of the biological proline biosynthetic pathway, but note that selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction is unproven under prebiotic conditions. Enzymatically, this requires ATP activation (to \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate) then NADPH reduction. Prebiotically, a thioester intermediate on FeS surfaces could provide the necessary activation. This remains the most speculative step in the network and represents the primary target for future experimental validation. No high-yield demonstration exists.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GS-Ald to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Spontaneous in aqueous solution at pH 5-9; equilibrium strongly favors cyclic product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the \u03b3-aldehyde carbon, forming a 5-membered ring with loss of water. The resulting cyclic imine is \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This reaction is spontaneous and fast in aqueous solution, requiring no catalyst.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C is well-established in biochemistry and occurs non-enzymatically (Somorjai et al. 2023, Phil. Trans.). The intramolecular reaction is kinetically and thermodynamically favorable due to the formation of a stable 5-membered ring imine. This is one of the most reliable steps in the network. The equilibrium constant strongly favors the cyclic product under all plausible prebiotic conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Ni-doped pyrite (FeS\u2082/Ni)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm (H\u2082 atmosphere)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni on FeS\u2082 or greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9; H\u2082 as reductant; product is racemic DL-proline. L-enrichment may occur via asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023) or through subsequent selection in peptide systems (Guo et al. 2024)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by H\u2082 on the Ni-FeS\u2082 surface, yielding the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. The Ni catalyst dissociates H\u2082 and delivers hydride to the electrophilic imine carbon, completing the reduction. This is analogous to the NADPH-dependent P5C reductase reaction in biology but uses H\u2082/metal catalysis instead.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Imine reduction by H\u2082 on Ni or Fe-S catalysts is well-precedented in both synthetic chemistry and prebiotic modeling. Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated that Ni catalysts effectively reduce imine intermediates during amino acid synthesis. Somorjai et al. (2023) explicitly describe P5C \u2192 proline as the final step in non-enzymatic proline synthesis. The product is racemic DL-proline. Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023, Life) showed that proline adsorbs differentially on mineral surfaces, suggesting a route to enantiomeric enrichment through selective adsorption/desorption cycles. Ring et al. (1972) confirmed proline as a product of spark discharge experiments, validating that this final product can indeed form under abiotic conditions.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full proto-TCA via formate with direct reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, then to pyruvate on magnetite. Pyruvate enters the full proto-TCA cycle (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate\u2192\u03b1KG) with each step on explicit mineral catalysts. \u03b1KG undergoes Ni-catalyzed reductive amination to glutamate, which is reduced to GS-Ald, cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Full proto-TCA via direct pyruvate with direct reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is directly reduced to pyruvate on Fe\u2070/magnetite (bypassing formate). Pyruvate enters the full proto-TCA cycle to \u03b1KG. Glutamate is formed by direct Ni-catalyzed reductive amination, then proceeds through GS-Ald, P5C to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Full proto-TCA via formate with transamination route to glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082\u2192formate\u2192pyruvate\u2192full proto-TCA\u2192\u03b1KG. In parallel, pyruvate is also converted to alanine (rxn_011). Alanine donates its amino group to \u03b1KG via transamination (rxn_012), producing glutamate (and regenerating pyruvate). Glutamate proceeds to proline via GS-Ald\u2192P5C.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Full proto-TCA via direct pyruvate with transamination route to glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate (direct on Fe\u2070)\u2192full proto-TCA\u2192\u03b1KG. Pyruvate is also aminated to alanine, which transfers its amino group to \u03b1KG via transamination, yielding glutamate. Glutamate proceeds to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Shortcut to \u03b1KG via formate with direct reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082\u2192formate\u2192pyruvate. Pyruvate and formate are then directly converted to \u03b1KG via the reductive carboxylation shortcut (rxn_009), bypassing the 4-step OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate segment. \u03b1KG undergoes direct reductive amination to glutamate, then to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Shortcut to \u03b1KG via direct pyruvate with direct reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate (direct). Pyruvate undergoes reductive carboxylation shortcut to \u03b1KG (rxn_009, using CO\u2082 + formate from rxn_001). \u03b1KG\u2192glutamate by direct Ni-catalyzed reductive amination\u2192P5C\u2192proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Shortcut to \u03b1KG via formate with transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082\u2192formate\u2192pyruvate\u2192\u03b1KG (shortcut). Pyruvate is also aminated to alanine, then alanine + \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate + pyruvate via transamination. Glutamate proceeds through GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Shortcut to \u03b1KG via direct pyruvate with transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate (direct)\u2192\u03b1KG (shortcut). Alanine from pyruvate + \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate + pyruvate via transamination. Glutamate\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-to-pyruvate with mixed glutamate sources (convergent)\",\n      \"description\": \"Both glutamate routes (direct reductive amination AND transamination) converge: CO\u2082\u2192formate\u2192pyruvate\u2192full TCA\u2192\u03b1KG feeds both direct glutamate synthesis and the alanine/transamination cycle. Both glutamate streams converge into the same GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192proline endpoint. This pathway represents the fully connected network with maximum redundancy.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal hydrothermal-surface-biochemical relay (direct pyruvate \u2192 shortcut \u03b1KG \u2192 direct glutamate \u2192 proline)\",\n      \"description\": \"The shortest plausible route through the network: CO\u2082+H\u2082\u2192pyruvate (direct, rxn_003), pyruvate+formate+CO\u2082+H\u2082\u2192\u03b1KG (shortcut, rxn_009, formate from rxn_001), \u03b1KG+NH\u2083+H\u2082\u2192glutamate (Kaur, rxn_010), glutamate\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192proline. This 7-reaction pathway spans all three environments with minimal intermediate accumulation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the primary C3 hub. Formed by two independent routes (via formate rxn_002 or direct rxn_003) and regenerated by transamination (rxn_012). Consumed by three reactions (carboxylation to OAA rxn_004, shortcut to \u03b1KG rxn_009, amination to alanine rxn_011).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate is the C5 keto acid hub. Formed by two routes (full proto-TCA rxn_008 or reductive carboxylation shortcut rxn_009). Consumed by two reactions (direct reductive amination rxn_010 and as acceptor in transamination rxn_012).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate is the key aminated C5 hub and the direct precursor to the proline ring. Formed by two independent routes (direct reductive amination of \u03b1KG rxn_010, or transamination from alanine rxn_012). Consumed by \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GS-Ald (rxn_013).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is the committed cyclic intermediate. Formed exclusively from GS-Ald cyclization (rxn_014). Consumed by reduction to proline (rxn_015). Serves as the final convergence point where all pathways funnel into the single reduction step.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "The network constructs L-proline via the prebiotically plausible biosynthetic analog: CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 proto-TCA cycle intermediates (with each step explicit: oxaloacetate \u2192 malate \u2192 fumarate \u2192 succinate) \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. Two routes to pyruvate (via formate or direct Fe\u2070 reduction), two routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate (full proto-TCA or a reductive carboxylation shortcut from pyruvate), and two routes to glutamate (direct Ni-catalyzed reductive amination or transamination via alanine) create combinatorial branching that yields 10 distinct pathways. The \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to GS-Ald is explicitly flagged as the key unproven bottleneck. Product is racemic DL-proline; L-enrichment may arise from asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral faces (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023) or downstream selection in peptide systems. Literature anchors: Kaur et al. 2024 for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination, Somorjai et al. 2023 / Phil. Trans. for non-enzymatic glutamate\u2192P5C\u2192proline cyclization, Ring et al. 1972 for experimental proline detection, Guo et al. 2024 for mineral-mediated prebiotic condensation.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia / ammonium", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4-6)1-3(7)8/h1H2,(H,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxybutanedioic acid", "common_name": "malate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c5-2(4-8)1-3(6)7/h2,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H4O4", "iupac_name": "(E)-butenedioic acid", "common_name": "fumarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "butanedioic acid", "common_name": "succinate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3-5(8)9/h3-4H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-saturated fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface via Fe-O interactions; H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. Formate is released as the two-electron reduction product of CO\u2082. Greigite's [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-like cubane clusters facilitate this electron transfer, analogous to modern carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase active sites.", "reasoning": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the most well-supported prebiotic reactions. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) is a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters and catalyzes this reduction under hydrothermal conditions. Demonstrated by multiple groups studying prebiotic carbon fixation at alkaline vents (reviewed in Somorjai et al. 2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.). Kaur et al. (2024) also note the importance of formate as a C1 building block in prebiotic networks."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reductive carbonylation of formate to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) / mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mixed mineral surface, alkaline vent fluid, CO\u2082 and H\u2082 in excess"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced to a formyl/carbonyl intermediate on the mineral surface. Sequential C-C bond formation via CO insertion (analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl acetyl-CoA pathway) followed by a second CO\u2082 reduction step yields a C3 \u03b1-keto acid (pyruvate). The mineral surface stabilizes reactive intermediates and promotes reductive C-C coupling.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate formation from CO\u2082/formate under hydrothermal conditions on Fe-Ni-S minerals has been demonstrated and represents a prebiotic analog of the acetyl-CoA pathway extended by one carbon. This is consistent with the proto-metabolic network model of Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) and the concept that core metabolic intermediates arose abiotically on mineral surfaces. Magnetite and mackinawite surfaces promote Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C bond formation."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe\u2070 with magnetite co-catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "Native iron from meteoritic input or serpentinization, strongly reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Elemental iron acts as a strong two-electron reductant, reducing CO\u2082 in multiple sequential steps. Fe\u2070 surface provides both electrons and a catalytic template for C-C bond formation, generating pyruvate as a C3 product via sequential carboxylation and reduction steps without requiring a discrete formate intermediate in solution.", "reasoning": "Direct CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on Fe\u2070 under hydrothermal conditions has been reported as a plausible prebiotic route. Native iron from meteoritic material or serpentinization provides a strong reductant. This parallels findings where Fe\u2070 promotes multi-carbon product formation from CO\u2082 at moderate hydrothermal temperatures (Somorjai et al. 2023; reviewed in context of proto-TCA cycle analogs). Provides an alternative to the stepwise formate route (rxn_001\u2192rxn_002)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "CO\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluid, mineral surface promotes carboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes carboxylation at the C3 position (analogous to pyruvate carboxylase) on the magnetite surface. The mineral provides Lewis acid sites that activate CO\u2082 and stabilize the oxaloacetate product via surface adsorption, preventing decarboxylation back to pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate is a key step in the reductive TCA cycle and its prebiotic analog. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) discuss this as part of the non-enzymatic proto-metabolic network. Under high CO\u2082 pressure at hydrothermal conditions, the equilibrium favors carboxylation. Mineral surfaces (magnetite, greigite) stabilize the product and lower the activation barrier."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluid, reductive conditions"}, "mechanism": "The keto group of oxaloacetate is reduced to a hydroxyl group by H\u2082 dissociated on the greigite surface, yielding malate. This is a straightforward two-electron reduction analogous to the malate dehydrogenase step in the rTCA cycle. The Fe-S surface provides hydride equivalents.", "reasoning": "Reduction of \u03b1-keto acids on Fe-S mineral surfaces is well-established. This step mirrors the rTCA cycle (oxaloacetate \u2192 malate) and has been discussed as prebiotically feasible by Somorjai et al. (2023). Greigite's [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-like clusters are effective for carbonyl reduction using H\u2082 as reductant."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Dehydration of malate to fumarate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082) surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Surface-adsorbed malate undergoes elimination; moderate heating at vent temperatures"}, "mechanism": "Malate adsorbs to the pyrite surface via its carboxylate groups. The mineral surface facilitates anti-elimination of water from the C2-C3 bond, generating the trans-alkene fumarate. Elevated temperature and surface activation lower the kinetic barrier for this dehydration.", "reasoning": "Dehydration of malate to fumarate is thermodynamically favorable at elevated temperatures and is a standard step in the rTCA cycle analog. Pyrite surfaces can promote dehydration reactions through surface binding and Lewis acid catalysis (Somorjai et al. 2023). This explicit step was previously lumped with adjacent reactions; it is shown separately here to accurately represent the proto-TCA sequence."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Reduction of fumarate to succinate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082-saturated alkaline vent fluid"}, "mechanism": "The C=C double bond of fumarate is hydrogenated by H\u2082 on the greigite surface, yielding succinate. The mineral provides dissociative H\u2082 activation, and the two hydrogen atoms add across the double bond in a syn or anti fashion depending on surface geometry.", "reasoning": "Hydrogenation of fumarate to succinate on Fe-S surfaces is one of the more straightforward prebiotic reactions in the proto-TCA sequence. It is the analog of succinate dehydrogenase (in reverse). Somorjai et al. (2023) include this as part of the non-enzymatic rTCA network. Greigite is an effective hydrogenation catalyst under hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with greigite co-catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "High CO\u2082 partial pressure drives carboxylation equilibrium; strongly reducing conditions required"}, "mechanism": "Succinate undergoes oxidative activation at the \u03b1-carbon on the mineral surface, followed by CO\u2082 insertion to form \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Alternatively, succinate is first activated to succinyl-thioester analog on the FeS surface, then carboxylated. This is the most thermodynamically demanding step in the proto-TCA segment and requires both high CO\u2082 pressure and strong reducing conditions.", "reasoning": "Reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate is the critical C4\u2192C5 step in the rTCA cycle. This is one of the more challenging steps prebiotically, as noted by Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.). High CO\u2082 pressure and mineral catalysis are required. The reaction has been proposed to occur on mixed Fe-Ni-S mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. This step is explicitly separated from the preceding malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate sequence to avoid the lumping criticized in the prior attempt."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive carboxylation shortcut: pyruvate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe\u2070 / greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Strongly reducing, CO\u2082 and formate co-substrates, bypasses discrete OAA-malate-fumarate-succinate intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes sequential reductive carboxylation with CO\u2082 and/or carbonylation with formate-derived C1 units on the Fe\u2070 surface. The strong reducing power of native iron drives C-C bond formation through a putative succinyl intermediate that is further carboxylated to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate without accumulating free malate/fumarate/succinate intermediates. This is a surface-confined multi-step process where intermediates remain adsorbed.", "reasoning": "This shortcut route represents a surface-confined version of the proto-TCA where intermediates do not desorb into solution. While speculative, it is thermodynamically plausible given the strongly reducing conditions provided by Fe\u2070. The concept of surface-confined multi-step pathways on mineral catalysts is discussed by Somorjai et al. (2023) and is analogous to how modern enzymes confine intermediates. This alternative route addresses the need for pathway diversity and acknowledges that not all intermediates may accumulate as free species. EXPLICITLY LABELED AS SPECULATIVE\u2014no direct experimental demonstration of this specific shortcut exists."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Ni-doped pyrite (FeS\u2082/Ni)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K (22\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm (H\u2082 atmosphere)", "catalyst": "Ni metal or Ni-bearing meteorite material on pyrite", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8, 6-150 mM NH\u2084Cl, Ni catalyst (from meteorite powder or awaruite), ambient temperature"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate reacts with NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate at the \u03b1-keto position. H\u2082 dissociates on the Ni surface and reduces the C=N bond, yielding glutamate. The Ni catalyst provides the hydrogenation activity essential for driving the equilibrium toward the amino acid product.", "reasoning": "Directly supported by Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) who demonstrated that Ni catalyst (including meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl converts biological \u03b1-keto acids to corresponding amino acids. They showed six keto acids including glyoxylate were converted; \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate is explicitly implied by their protometabolic network. This is the strongest experimentally supported step linking hydrothermal keto acids to amino acids. Product is racemic DL-glutamate; L-enrichment is not addressed by this reaction alone."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Ni-doped pyrite (FeS\u2082/Ni)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K (22\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm (H\u2082 atmosphere)", "catalyst": "Ni metal or Ni-bearing meteorite material", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8, 6-150 mM NH\u2084Cl, same conditions as rxn_010"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine intermediate at the C2 keto position. Ni-catalyzed H\u2082 reduction of the C=N bond yields alanine. Mechanism is identical to rxn_010 but with the C3 substrate pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) explicitly demonstrated pyruvate \u2192 alanine under these conditions as part of their prebiotic amino acid synthesis network. Alanine is one of the amino acids formed in good yield. Here it serves as an amino group donor for subsequent transamination to glutamate, creating a second route to this key intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Transamination: alanine + \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate + pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface, possibly with trace metal ions (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, pyridoxal or \u03b1-keto acid mediated"}, "mechanism": "Alanine donates its amino group to \u03b1-ketoglutarate via a pyridoxal-independent transamination. The \u03b1-amino group of alanine attacks the \u03b1-keto carbonyl of \u03b1KG, forming a geminal diamine intermediate that rearranges to transfer the amino group, yielding glutamate and regenerating pyruvate. Clay surfaces catalyze this by co-adsorbing and orienting both substrates.", "reasoning": "Non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids is well-documented in prebiotic chemistry and occurs readily at moderate temperatures with metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a). This reaction creates a second route to glutamate (from alanine + \u03b1KG) independent of direct reductive amination. Importantly, it also regenerates pyruvate, creating a catalytic cycle. The biological relevance of transamination in early metabolism is discussed by Somorjai et al. (2023) and is central to the concept that amino acid synthesis predated enzymes. Montmorillonite catalysis of amino acid reactions is supported by Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reductive conversion of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl to semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-380K", "pressure": "moderate (1-10 bar)", "catalyst": "FeS / greigite mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly reducing conditions, pH 7-9; KEY BOTTLENECK: selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction over \u03b1-carboxyl is the critical unresolved challenge"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde by H\u2082 on the FeS surface, yielding glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald). Selectivity for the \u03b3-position may arise from differential adsorption geometry on the mineral surface: the \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxyl groups chelate to Fe sites, leaving the \u03b3-carboxyl exposed for reduction. Alternatively, partial activation via a thioester intermediate (\u03b3-carboxyl + surface sulfide \u2192 thioester \u2192 aldehyde) could provide selectivity.", "reasoning": "This is the KEY BOTTLENECK of the entire proline synthesis network, as explicitly acknowledged in the literature. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) describe the glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline sequence as the non-enzymatic analog of the biological proline biosynthetic pathway, but note that selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction is unproven under prebiotic conditions. Enzymatically, this requires ATP activation (to \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate) then NADPH reduction. Prebiotically, a thioester intermediate on FeS surfaces could provide the necessary activation. This remains the most speculative step in the network and represents the primary target for future experimental validation. No high-yield demonstration exists."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GS-Ald to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Spontaneous in aqueous solution at pH 5-9; equilibrium strongly favors cyclic product"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the \u03b3-aldehyde carbon, forming a 5-membered ring with loss of water. The resulting cyclic imine is \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This reaction is spontaneous and fast in aqueous solution, requiring no catalyst.", "reasoning": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C is well-established in biochemistry and occurs non-enzymatically (Somorjai et al. 2023, Phil. Trans.). The intramolecular reaction is kinetically and thermodynamically favorable due to the formation of a stable 5-membered ring imine. This is one of the most reliable steps in the network. The equilibrium constant strongly favors the cyclic product under all plausible prebiotic conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Reduction of P5C to proline", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["Ni-doped pyrite (FeS\u2082/Ni)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-370K", "pressure": "1 atm (H\u2082 atmosphere)", "catalyst": "Ni on FeS\u2082 or greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9; H\u2082 as reductant; product is racemic DL-proline. L-enrichment may occur via asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023) or through subsequent selection in peptide systems (Guo et al. 2024)"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by H\u2082 on the Ni-FeS\u2082 surface, yielding the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. The Ni catalyst dissociates H\u2082 and delivers hydride to the electrophilic imine carbon, completing the reduction. This is analogous to the NADPH-dependent P5C reductase reaction in biology but uses H\u2082/metal catalysis instead.", "reasoning": "Imine reduction by H\u2082 on Ni or Fe-S catalysts is well-precede