well-architected synthesis network with excellent topology (15 molecules, 15 reactions, 4 hubs, 4 convergence points, 10 pathways) and strong literature grounding. The strategy of mimicking the biological glutamate\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192proline pathway is logical and well-cited (Kaur et al. 2024 for reductive amination; Ring et al. 1972 for proline detection; Somorjai/Phil. Trans. for non-enzymatic cyclization). The environmental flow (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical) is coherent and mineral catalysts (greigite, pyrite, native iron, Ni) are properly specified for the first two stages. Hub molecules (pyruvate, \u03b1KG, glutamate, P5C) are appropriately chosen with adequate connectivity.\\n\\nHowever, the network has a critical and honestly acknowledged weakness: rxn_013 (selective reduction of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl to semialdehyde) lacks experimental support under prebiotic conditions. In biology, this requires ATP activation plus NADPH reduction (enzymes \u03b3-glutamyl kinase + \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase). No mineral catalyst or simple reductant has been shown to achieve this selectivity prebiotically. This bottleneck affects ALL 10 pathways and prevents any from reaching the 0.80 approval threshold. Additional concerns include: rxn_008 (succinate\u2192\u03b1KG carboxylation without CoA activation), rxn_009 (mechanistically unclear shortcut), and rxn_012 (transamination without PLP analog). The network correctly notes that the product would be racemic DL-proline.\\n\\nThe network's greatest strengths are its honest acknowledgment of limitations, its excellent use of combinatorial branching to explore alternatives, and its thorough literature alignment. The research correctly identifies that no dedicated high-yield prebiotic route to proline exists, and this network represents about the best that current knowledge can support. To improve: focus on resolving the \u03b3-carboxyl reduction step\u2014perhaps via thioester intermediates (anal