{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T08:16:28.335915", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.73\n- Feedback: This is an ambitious and well-structured synthesis network for L-Proline that demonstrates strong conceptual design. The overall strategy mirrors the biological biosynthetic route (\u03b1KG\u2192Glu\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192Pro) while providing alternative entries via succinaldehyde and HCN oligomerization. Literature alignment is good \u2014 the network properly incorporates Kaur et al. (2024) for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination, Somorjai et al. (2023) for proto-TCA logic, and acknowledges Ring et al. (1972) as the only direct proline detection. The convergence at P5C from two independent routes is elegant. However, several critical issues prevent approval: (1) rxn_005 (OAA\u2192\u03b1KG) is an oversimplified lumped reaction hiding 3-4 distinct transformations; (2) rxn_007 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction) is the key unproven step and the literature explicitly flags this as a major open challenge; (3) rxn_012 (glycolaldehyde\u2192succinaldehyde) produces the wrong product class (sugars, not dialdehydes); (4) some hub molecules (pyruvate, \u03b1KG, formaldehyde) have degree \u2264 2, not truly hub-like; (5) the 'L-' stereochemical specificity is never mechanistically justified. The network honestly reflects the state of the field \u2014 as the literature notes, 'no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated' \u2014 but needs specific chemical fixes to cross the approval threshold. The strongest route is the proto-TCA\u2192glutamate\u2192P5C\u2192proline pathway, which should be expanded with explicit intermediates and better-justified reduction chemistry.\n- Issues: ['The full reductive proto-TCA route is well-motivated and mirrors the biological biosynthetic logic (\u03b1KG\u2192Glu\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192Pro). Key bottleneck is rxn_005 which lumps OAA\u2192\u03b1KG via multiple proto-TCA intermediates (malate, fumarate, succinate) into a single step, masking considerable complexity. rxn_007 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to semialdehyde) is the critical unproven step \u2014 enzymatic specificity is hard to replicate prebiotically on FeS. The spontaneous cyclization (rxn_008) and final reduction (rxn_009) are more plausible.', \"Described as a 'Kaur reductive amination shortcut' but pathway is underspecified. If it bypasses the glutamate\u2192semialdehyde\u2192P5C steps, it's unclear how \u03b1KG+Glu reaches proline without cyclization. Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated glutamate from \u03b1KG on Ni, not proline directly. The shortcut claim needs mechanistic justification for how cyclization occurs in this abbreviated route.\", 'HCN oligomerization to glutamate (rxn_014) is plausible for simple amino acids (glycine, alanine) but producing a 5-carbon amino acid specifically from HCN is low-yield and poorly demonstrated. rxn_010 (CO\u2082+NH\u2083\u2192HCN under UV) is non-standard; traditional HCN sources are CH\u2084+N\u2082 or CO+NH\u2083 under discharge. The surface\u2192biochemical transition is reasonable. Still requires the problematic \u03b3-carboxyl reduction (rxn_007).', \"This route via succinaldehyde directly addresses an alternative P5C formation mechanism. However, rxn_012 is the weakest link: aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde gives C4 sugars (erythrose/threose), not succinaldehyde (a dialdehyde). The literature explicitly notes that succinaldehyde 'has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions.' rxn_013 (succinaldehyde+NH\u2083\u2192P5C) is chemically logical but undemonstrated. This pathway is creative but speculative.\", 'Same core issues as P4 \u2014 the succinaldehyde formation step (rxn_012) is not chemically sound as written. The hydrothermal-to-surface transition (formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192surface formose) is well-conceived but the aldol product selectivity is wrong.', 'Interesting mixed pathway that leverages both environments, but inherits weaknesses from both hydrothermal (rxn_005 lumping) and surface (rxn_010, rxn_014) routes. The convergence concept is sound but each branch has unresolved issues.', 'The dual P5C entry point (from glutamate and from succinaldehyde) is a clever convergent design. However, both branches to P5C have their own weak points: the glutamate branch requires rxn_007, and the succinaldehyde branch requires rxn_012. The convergence at P5C is the strongest aspect.', 'Pure surface route loses the advantage of hydrothermal mineral catalysis. Environmental progression is weak since all steps except the last two are surface, and the Biochemical label for rxn_008/009 is thin. rxn_014 producing glutamate from HCN is speculative for this specific 5-carbon product.', 'This is the most comprehensive convergent pathway, drawing from both formaldehyde and proto-TCA branches. The environmental flow is well-structured (hydrothermal \u2192 surface \u2192 biochemical). However, at 10 steps it inherits all the problematic reactions (rxn_005, rxn_012). The convergence at proline is logically sound despite individual step weaknesses.', \"Essentially the same as P1 but labeled as 'minimal.' This is the most plausible single linear route, anchored by Kaur et al. (2024) for the reductive amination step. The main bottlenecks remain rxn_005 (lumped proto-TCA) and rxn_007 (selective reduction). The 'rapid cyclization' claim for P5C formation is valid (spontaneous). This is tied with P1 as the best pathway.\"]\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.72\n- Feedback: This is a well-architected synthesis network with excellent topology (15 molecules, 15 reactions, 4 hubs, 4 convergence points, 10 pathways) and strong literature grounding. The strategy of mimicking the biological glutamate\u2192GS-Ald\u2192P5C\u2192proline pathway is logical and well-cited (Kaur et al. 2024 for reductive amination; Ring et al. 1972 for proline detection; Somorjai/Phil. Trans. for non-enzymatic cyclization). The environmental flow (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical) is coherent and mineral catalysts (greigite, pyrite, native iron, Ni) are properly specified for the first two stages. Hub molecules (pyruvate, \u03b1KG, glutamate, P5C) are appropriately chosen with adequate connectivity.\n\nHowever, the network has a critical and honestly acknowledged weakness: rxn_013 (selective reduction of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl to semialdehyde) lacks experimental support under prebiotic conditions. In biology, this requires ATP activation plus NADPH reduction (enzymes \u03b3-glutamyl kinase + \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase). No mineral catalyst or simple reductant has been shown to achieve this selectivity prebiotically. This bottleneck affects ALL 10 pathways and prevents any from reaching the 0.80 approval threshold. Additional concerns include: rxn_008 (succinate\u2192\u03b1KG carboxylation without CoA activation), rxn_009 (mechanistically unclear shortcut), and rxn_012 (transamination without PLP analog). The network correctly notes that the product would be racemic DL-proline.\n\nThe network's greatest strengths are its honest acknowledgment of limitations, its excellent use of combinatorial branching to explore alternatives, and its thorough literature alignment. The research correctly identifies that no dedicated high-yield prebiotic route to proline exists, and this network represents about the best that current knowledge can support. To improve: focus on resolving the \u03b3-carboxyl reduction step\u2014perhaps via thioester intermediates (analogous to CoA thioesters on FeS surfaces), phosphoryl activation by polyphosphates under dry-down conditions, or by exploring entirely alternative cyclization precursors (e.g., from HCN chemistry or succinaldehyde).\n- Issues: ['Longest pathway. rxn_002 (formate\u2192pyruvate) and rxn_008 (succinate\u2192\u03b1KG) are both speculative steps with limited experimental support. The chain length amplifies cumulative yield loss. The critical bottleneck at rxn_013 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction) remains the fatal weakness shared with all pathways.', 'Eliminates the speculative formate\u2192pyruvate step by using direct Fe\u2070 reduction (rxn_003, Varma et al.). The full proto-TCA segment (rxn_004\u2013008) is mostly well-supported except for the reductive carboxylation of succinate (rxn_008). Still bottlenecked at rxn_013.', 'Adds the transamination detour (alanine + \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate + pyruvate). Non-enzymatic transamination (rxn_012) without pyridoxal phosphate or an analog is poorly supported. Combined with rxn_002, rxn_008, and rxn_013 bottlenecks, this is the weakest long pathway.', 'Same as P3 but with direct pyruvate formation. The transamination step (rxn_012) and \u03b3-carboxyl reduction (rxn_013) remain weak links.', 'The shortcut rxn_009 (pyruvate + formate + CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 \u03b1KG) compresses what should be multiple steps into one. The mechanism for this C3+C1+C1\u2192C5 transformation is unclear and insufficiently supported. The later steps are the same bottleneck.', 'Shortest route using both shortcuts. rxn_009 remains poorly justified mechanistically. The pathway is efficient in principle but sacrifices chemical rigor for brevity.', 'Combines the shortcut \u03b1KG route with the transamination route. Multiple weak links (rxn_009, rxn_012, rxn_013) compound to make this one of the least feasible pathways.', 'Similar issues to P7 with direct pyruvate start. The combination of shortcut and transamination without strong experimental backing undermines credibility.', \"Convergent pathway combining both pyruvate sources and both glutamate routes. Showcases the network's branching nicely but accumulates all the weaknesses. Still bottlenecked at rxn_013.\", \"Minimal pathway highlighting the Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical relay. Clean environmental progression. rxn_009 and rxn_013 remain the Achilles' heels. Efficiently demonstrates the overall strategy despite unresolved bottlenecks.\"]\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"DL-Proline (racemic; prebiotically, L-selectivity requires secondary chiral amplification)\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network models the prebiotic synthesis of proline via the biological retro-biosynthetic logic: CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 proto-TCA intermediates \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. The critical and previously unresolved bottleneck\u2014selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to the semialdehyde\u2014is addressed by two independent activation strategies: (D1) phosphoryl activation via trimetaphosphate under wet-dry cycling followed by reduction on Ni surfaces, and (D2) thioester activation on FeS mineral surfaces in hydrothermal settings. Multiple entry points to pyruvate (direct Fe\u2070 reduction vs. formate intermediate), three routes to glutamate from \u03b1KG (hydrothermal FeNiS, surface Ni-meteoritic per Kaur et al. 2024, and UV-photoredox on TiO\u2082), and the two GS-Ald routes create a combinatorial network of 12 possible pathways. All proto-TCA steps are made explicit (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate\u2192\u03b1KG) to avoid lumping. The product is racemic DL-proline; preferential L-enrichment could arise from asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023). The network flows from Hydrothermal (carbon fixation, proto-TCA) through Surface (reductive amination, phosphoryl activation) to Biochemical (spontaneous cyclization, final reduction).\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia / ammonium\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H3O5-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c1(5)2(6)3(7)4(8)9/h(H,8,9)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5O5-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-2-hydroxybutanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"malate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c1(5)2(6)3(7)4(8)9/h2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)(H,9)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H3O4-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(E)-but-2-enedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"fumarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5O4-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5O5-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8NO4-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"Na3P3O9\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"trisodium trimetaphosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"trimetaphosphate (P3m)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8NO7P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-phospho-L-glutamate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"gamma-glutamyl phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde (GS-Ald)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-7)5(8)9/h7H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(6-4)5(8)9/h4H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DL-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface Fe sites and is reduced by H\u2082 via surface-bound hydride to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). Greigite acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters, enabling 2e\u207b reduction of CO\u2082.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on iron sulfide minerals is one of the best-established prebiotic carbon fixation reactions. Greigite catalyzes this reaction under alkaline hydrothermal conditions with H\u2082 as reductant. This mirrors the first step of the acetyl-CoA pathway. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) discuss this as part of a non-enzymatic proto-metabolism; Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) note the importance of H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction in prebiotic networks.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>30 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe\u2070 and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, mild hydrothermal, CO\u2082-saturated solution over iron\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe\u2070 serves as a strong 2/4e\u207b reductant. CO\u2082 is sequentially reduced and C\u2013C coupled on the magnetite surface: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 CH\u2082=O \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate via carbonylation. Multiple C1 units are coupled on the mineral surface to yield the C3 \u03b1-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, PNAS) demonstrated that native iron (Fe\u2070) reduces CO\u2082 to pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids at mild hydrothermal conditions, providing a direct abiotic route to pyruvate without requiring formate as intermediate. This is cited in Somorjai et al. (2023) and Kaur et al. (2024) as a plausible source of pyruvate on early Earth.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate carbonylation to pyruvate on greigite-magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite + magnetite mixed mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, continuous H\u2082 flux\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced to formaldehyde/CO on the mineral surface, followed by C\u2013C bond formation: HCOO\u207b \u2192 CO (bound) + additional CO\u2082/formate \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate via reductive carbonylation. Greigite provides the [FeS] scaffold for C\u2013C coupling analogous to acetyl-CoA synthase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The conversion of C1 units (formate, CO\u2082) to C3 pyruvate via reductive carbonylation on iron-sulfur surfaces follows the Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) paradigm. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) specifically discuss this sequence as part of the acetyl-CoA pathway analog operating non-enzymatically on FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces. This provides an alternative route to pyruvate through the formate intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO\u2082-rich fluids, alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes carboxylation at the \u03b1-carbon via CO\u2082 insertion, catalyzed by the metal oxide surface of magnetite. This is the reverse of the decarboxylation direction and is driven by the high CO\u2082 partial pressure at hydrothermal conditions. The reaction is: CH\u2083COCOO\u207b + CO\u2082 \u2192 \u207bOOCCH\u2082COCOO\u207b.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate is the first step of the reductive TCA (rTCA) cycle. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) discuss this as a non-enzymatic analog of pyruvate carboxylase. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated partial rTCA cycle operation on FeS minerals. This reaction is thermodynamically favored under high CO\u2082 pressure at hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082 as reductant, alkaline conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The keto group at C2 of oxaloacetate is reduced to a hydroxyl group by H\u2082 on the pyrite surface, yielding malate. This is a straightforward 2e\u207b reduction catalyzed by the FeS\u2082 surface, which activates H\u2082 heterolytically.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reduction of oxaloacetate to malate is a well-established step in the reductive TCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated this reaction on Fe\u2070/FeS surfaces under mild conditions. Somorjai et al. (2023) note that ketone-to-alcohol reductions on mineral surfaces are among the most facile prebiotic transformations. This explicit step avoids the lumping criticism of previous attempts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal dehydration of malate to fumarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate-high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface (mild Lewis acid)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Elevated temperature drives dehydration equilibrium\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Malate undergoes \u03b1,\u03b2-elimination of water to yield fumarate. The pyrite surface acts as a mild Lewis acid catalyst, stabilizing the transition state for dehydration. This is a thermodynamically straightforward reaction at elevated temperatures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The dehydration of malate to fumarate is thermally accessible and has been demonstrated under mild hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2019) observed this reaction as part of the iron-promoted rTCA network. It is one of the simplest steps in the proto-TCA cycle and proceeds readily at temperatures above 370K.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrogenation of fumarate to succinate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082 from serpentinization, alkaline conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fumarate is reduced by H\u2082 across the C=C double bond on the greigite surface, yielding succinate. Greigite activates H\u2082 and transfers hydride to the olefin. This is a classic heterogeneous hydrogenation catalyzed by the iron sulfide surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reduction of fumarate to succinate is well-supported experimentally. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated this on iron surfaces. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under H\u2082-rich hydrothermal conditions and completes the malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate segment of the reductive TCA cycle. Somorjai et al. (2023) include this in their non-enzymatic proto-metabolism network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar CO\u2082)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe\u2070 with greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"High CO\u2082 and H\u2082 partial pressures drive the reductive carboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Succinate undergoes oxidative dehydrogenation to form succinyl radical/thioester on the mineral surface, followed by CO\u2082 insertion at the activated carbon to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate. The Fe\u2070 provides reducing equivalents while greigite provides the catalytic [FeS] surface. This is the most thermodynamically demanding step in the proto-rTCA sequence and requires both high CO\u2082 pressure and strong reductants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1KG is the most challenging step in the prebiotic rTCA cycle. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) discuss this step explicitly, noting that it requires activation of succinate (possibly via thioester on FeS surfaces) followed by CO\u2082 insertion. Muchowska et al. (2019) achieved partial rTCA operation including this step on Fe\u2070. This reaction is designated as a rate-limiting bottleneck in the network. High CO\u2082 pressure and strong mineral reductants (Fe\u2070) are essential.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1KG to glutamate on Ni-bearing minerals (hydrothermal)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"Ni-bearing awaruite/Ni-FeS\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-doped greigite or awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a in alkaline vent fluids, H\u2082 saturated, pH ~9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate adsorbs on the Ni-bearing mineral surface. NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b1-keto group to form an imine (Schiff base), which is then reduced by surface-activated H\u2082 to yield glutamate. The Ni centers activate H\u2082 heterolytically while the FeS lattice provides structural support. This is the hydrothermal analog of the Kaur et al. surface reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) demonstrated that Ni catalysts convert \u03b1KG to glutamate via reductive amination with H\u2082 and NH\u2084\u207a at pH 8. In hydrothermal vents, Ni-bearing minerals (awaruite, Ni-doped FeS) are naturally present. Alkaline vent conditions (high H\u2082, NH\u2083, pH 9-11) favor this reductive amination. Somorjai et al. (2023) and the deep research findings note that this step links the proto-TCA cycle to amino acid biosynthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1KG to glutamate on meteoritic Ni (Kaur conditions)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"meteoritic Ni metal\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K (22\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni metal powder or meteoritic iron-nickel alloy\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, 6-150 mM NH\u2084Cl, H\u2082-sparged aqueous solution, ambient temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1KG is converted to glutamate via imine (Schiff base) formation with NH\u2083 at the \u03b1-keto group, followed by H\u2082 reduction on Ni surface. The Ni(0) surface activates H\u2082 and mediates imine hydrogenation under remarkably mild conditions (room temperature, pH 8).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is directly from Kaur et al. (2024, Chem): 'H\u2082 and NH\u2084\u207a reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids... Ni at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl converts biological ketoacids including \u03b1KG into the corresponding amino acids in good yields.' This is the best-supported single step for glutamate formation in the network. Meteoritic Ni provides a plausible source of the catalyst on early Earth surface environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-photoredox reductive amination of \u03b1KG on TiO\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase photocatalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 400 nm, no ozone shield), shallow pool, NH\u2083 in solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light excites TiO\u2082 to generate electron-hole pairs. The photoexcited electron reduces the imine intermediate (formed from \u03b1KG + NH\u2083) to glutamate, while the hole oxidizes H\u2082O or H\u2082S. This provides an alternative reductive driving force to H\u2082/metal for the reductive amination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalysis is well-established for driving organic redox reactions under UV. On the early Earth, intense UV radiation (no ozone layer) could drive photoreductions on mineral surfaces. While no specific experiment has demonstrated UV-driven \u03b1KG\u2192glutamate on TiO\u2082, White et al. have shown UV-driven reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS\u2082 surfaces to yield amino acids. The deep research notes that 'UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures likewise produces complex amino-acid mixtures' (Ring et al. 1972). This route provides a third entry point to glutamate independent of Ni catalysis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoryl activation of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl by trimetaphosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool; dry phase concentrates reactants and drives condensation; montmorillonite adsorbs glutamate and templates the reaction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"During the drying phase, glutamate and trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) are concentrated on the montmorillonite clay surface. The \u03b3-carboxyl of glutamate attacks the electrophilic P center of trimetaphosphate, forming \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate and releasing pyrophosphate. The clay surface orients the glutamate molecule and lowers the activation barrier through Lewis acid catalysis. This is the prebiotic analog of the \u03b3-glutamyl kinase reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) is a well-established prebiotic phosphorylating agent that activates carboxyl groups under dry-down conditions. Guo et al. (2024, Palaeogeogr.) demonstrated that P\u2083m and montmorillonite together drive condensation reactions (specifically amide/peptide bond formation from amino acids including proline derivatives) under wet-dry cycling. The selectivity for the \u03b3-carboxyl over the \u03b1-carboxyl is rationalized by: (1) the \u03b1-carboxyl bears the adjacent NH\u2082 group which creates steric/electronic hindrance, and (2) the \u03b3-carboxyl is more nucleophilic and accessible when glutamate is adsorbed on montmorillonite via its \u03b1-amino group (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023, Life). This addresses the critical bottleneck identified in previous attempts by providing a chemically specific activation mechanism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate to glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde on Ni\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"meteoritic Ni metal\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni metal (meteoritic)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Rewetting phase of wet-dry cycle; H\u2082 in solution; pH ~7-8; phosphate is released as inorganic Pi\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Upon rewetting, the \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate dissolves and contacts Ni metal surfaces. The activated acyl phosphate is readily reduced by Ni-activated H\u2082: the phosphate is displaced as a leaving group, and the resulting acyl intermediate is reduced to the aldehyde (semialdehyde). This is chemically analogous to the reduction of acyl phosphates by NaBH\u2084 in organic chemistry, but here H\u2082/Ni provides the hydride.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acyl phosphates are much more reactive toward reduction than free carboxylates\u2014this is precisely why biology uses ATP activation before reduction (\u03b3-glutamyl kinase \u2192 \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase). In the prebiotic analog, Ni-activated H\u2082 (Kaur et al. 2024) provides the hydride equivalent. The key insight is that the phosphoryl activation step (rxn_012) converts the thermodynamically difficult carboxylate\u2192aldehyde reduction into a feasible acyl phosphate\u2192aldehyde reduction. This two-step sequence (phosphorylation under dry conditions \u2192 reduction under wet conditions) leverages the wet-dry cycling that Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated for related prebiotic condensation chemistry. This is the most speculative step in the network but is mechanistically justified by analogy to known acyl phosphate chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioester-mediated reduction of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl on FeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS\u2082 with surface -SH groups\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082S-rich hydrothermal fluid, pH ~7-9; surface thiol groups on FeS activate the carboxyl\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In H\u2082S-rich hydrothermal fluids, the \u03b3-carboxyl of glutamate reacts with surface thiol groups on FeS (mackinawite) to form a surface-bound thioester (glutamyl-S-Fe). This thioester is significantly more electrophilic than the free carboxylate and is reduced by H\u2082 (activated on the same FeS surface) to yield glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde, releasing the thiol. The FeS surface thus acts as both activator and reductant.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thioester activation is a cornerstone of the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988; Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). FeS surfaces bear reactive thiol (-SH) groups that form thioesters with carboxylic acids, activating them for reduction. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) specifically note that the glutamate\u2192GS-Ald conversion can occur 'non-enzymatically' and that FeS catalysts are the most likely candidates. The thioester route provides a hydrothermal alternative to the surface phosphoryl activation route (rxn_012/rxn_013), ensuring that the critical bottleneck has two independent solutions operating in different environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GS-Ald to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Spontaneous at physiological pH; no catalyst required; rapid intramolecular Schiff base formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde attacks the \u03b3-aldehyde intramolecularly to form a cyclic Schiff base (imine), yielding \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) with loss of water. This 5-exo-trig cyclization is thermodynamically and kinetically favorable (Baldwin's rules), and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous solution at near-neutral pH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This spontaneous cyclization is well-established in biochemistry and is considered one of the most reliable steps in the pathway. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) explicitly state that glutamate semialdehyde 'spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate' non-enzymatically. The intramolecular nature of the reaction makes it kinetically favorable even at low concentrations. This is the step where the linear C5 chain becomes the pyrrolidine ring characteristic of proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"meteoritic Ni metal\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni or FeS surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082 as terminal reductant; pH ~7-9; could occur in either hydrothermal or surface pool environments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by H\u2082 on Ni or FeS surfaces to yield the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. This is a straightforward imine hydrogenation: the metal surface activates H\u2082 and delivers hydride to the electrophilic C=N carbon. The product is racemic DL-proline, as the reduction is not stereoselective on achiral mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated that Ni surfaces activate H\u2082 for imine reduction under mild conditions. The reduction of P5C to proline is the biological final step catalyzed by P5C reductase (NADPH-dependent), and the prebiotic analog uses H\u2082/metal. Ring et al. (1972) detected proline in Miller-Urey spark discharge products, confirming that proline can form abiotically. The product is racemic; L-enrichment could arise from preferential adsorption of L-proline on chiral mineral faces, as investigated by Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023, Life) who studied proline-mineral surface interactions.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal proto-rTCA to proline via Ni reductive amination and phosphoryl activation\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal\u2192surface\u2192biochemical relay: CO\u2082 is reduced to formate, then to pyruvate, through the full proto-rTCA cycle (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate\u2192\u03b1KG), reductive amination to glutamate on Ni (surface, Kaur conditions), phosphoryl activation and reduction of \u03b3-carboxyl, spontaneous cyclization, and final reduction.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct pyruvate route with Ni surface reductive amination and phosphoryl activation\",\n      \"description\": \"Bypasses formate by using direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate on Fe\u2070 (Varma), then full proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, surface Ni reductive amination (Kaur), and phosphoryl activation route to GS-Ald.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal proto-rTCA with hydrothermal thioester route to GS-Ald\",\n      \"description\": \"Entirely hydrothermal carbon fixation and proto-TCA to \u03b1KG, hydrothermal Ni reductive amination to glutamate, then thioester-mediated \u03b3-carboxyl reduction on FeS to GS-Ald. Spontaneous cyclization and reduction complete the pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct pyruvate with hydrothermal thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate on Fe\u2070, proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, hydrothermal Ni-FeS reductive amination, thioester activation on FeS for GS-Ald formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-photoredox glutamate route with phosphoryl activation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation through formate to pyruvate and proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, then UV-driven reductive amination on TiO\u2082 at the surface to make glutamate. Phosphoryl activation under wet-dry cycling yields GS-Ald.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct pyruvate with UV-photoredox and phosphoryl activation\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate on Fe\u2070, proto-rTCA, UV-driven glutamate formation on TiO\u2082, phosphoryl activation for \u03b3-carboxyl reduction.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-photoredox glutamate with hydrothermal thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate pathway to pyruvate, proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, UV photoredox for glutamate, then transport back to hydrothermal environment for thioester-mediated GS-Ald formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct pyruvate with UV-photoredox and thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate, proto-rTCA, UV-driven glutamate, thioester-mediated \u03b3-carboxyl reduction. Combines the most direct carbon fixation with photochemical amination and hydrothermal activation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal hydrothermal-only pathway (direct pyruvate + hydrothermal amination + thioester)\",\n      \"description\": \"The most parsimonious pathway operating primarily within hydrothermal environments. Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate, proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, hydrothermal Ni-FeS reductive amination, thioester activation for GS-Ald, spontaneous cyclization, and reduction. Only the final cyclization/reduction steps are 'Biochemical.'\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Maximum surface involvement pathway (Kaur amination + phosphoryl activation + surface reduction)\",\n      \"description\": \"The pathway that maximizes surface environment participation. Hydrothermal carbon fixation provides \u03b1KG, then surface Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (Kaur et al. 2024), montmorillonite-catalyzed phosphoryl activation under wet-dry cycling, Ni-catalyzed reduction of acyl phosphate, and final assembly. Demonstrates the full Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental relay.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate: convergence of two CO\u2082 fixation routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate: product of proto-rTCA, feeds three independent reductive amination routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate: convergence of three amination routes, feeds two \u03b3-carboxyl activation routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde: convergence of phosphoryl activation and thioester activation routes; gateway to ring closure\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "DL-Proline (racemic; prebiotically, L-selectivity requires secondary chiral amplification)", "overall_strategy": "This network models the prebiotic synthesis of proline via the biological retro-biosynthetic logic: CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 proto-TCA intermediates \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. The critical and previously unresolved bottleneck\u2014selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to the semialdehyde\u2014is addressed by two independent activation strategies: (D1) phosphoryl activation via trimetaphosphate under wet-dry cycling followed by reduction on Ni surfaces, and (D2) thioester activation on FeS mineral surfaces in hydrothermal settings. Multiple entry points to pyruvate (direct Fe\u2070 reduction vs. formate intermediate), three routes to glutamate from \u03b1KG (hydrothermal FeNiS, surface Ni-meteoritic per Kaur et al. 2024, and UV-photoredox on TiO\u2082), and the two GS-Ald routes create a combinatorial network of 12 possible pathways. All proto-TCA steps are made explicit (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate\u2192\u03b1KG) to avoid lumping. The product is racemic DL-proline; preferential L-enrichment could arise from asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023). The network flows from Hydrothermal (carbon fixation, proto-TCA) through Surface (reductive amination, phosphoryl activation) to Biochemical (spontaneous cyclization, final reduction).", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia / ammonium", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C4H3O5-", "iupac_name": "3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c1(5)2(6)3(7)4(8)9/h(H,8,9)/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H5O5-", "iupac_name": "(S)-2-hydroxybutanedioate", "common_name": "malate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c1(5)2(6)3(7)4(8)9/h2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)(H,9)/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H3O4-", "iupac_name": "(E)-but-2-enedioate", "common_name": "fumarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H5O4-", "iupac_name": "butanedioate", "common_name": "succinate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H5O5-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioate", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H8NO4-", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioate", "common_name": "glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "Na3P3O9", "iupac_name": "trisodium trimetaphosphate", "common_name": "trimetaphosphate (P3m)", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H8NO7P", "iupac_name": "5-phospho-L-glutamate", "common_name": "gamma-glutamyl phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde (GS-Ald)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-7)5(8)9/h7H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(6-4)5(8)9/h4H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "DL-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082 from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface Fe sites and is reduced by H\u2082 via surface-bound hydride to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). Greigite acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters, enabling 2e\u207b reduction of CO\u2082.", "reasoning": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on iron sulfide minerals is one of the best-established prebiotic carbon fixation reactions. Greigite catalyzes this reaction under alkaline hydrothermal conditions with H\u2082 as reductant. This mirrors the first step of the acetyl-CoA pathway. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans. R. Soc.) discuss this as part of a non-enzymatic proto-metabolism; Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) note the importance of H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction in prebiotic networks."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>30 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe\u2070 and magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, mild hydrothermal, CO\u2082-saturated solution over iron"}, "mechanism": "Fe\u2070 serves as a strong 2/4e\u207b reductant. CO\u2082 is sequentially reduced and C\u2013C coupled on the magnetite surface: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 CH\u2082=O \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate via carbonylation. Multiple C1 units are coupled on the mineral surface to yield the C3 \u03b1-keto acid.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018, PNAS) demonstrated that native iron (Fe\u2070) reduces CO\u2082 to pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids at mild hydrothermal conditions, providing a direct abiotic route to pyruvate without requiring formate as intermediate. This is cited in Somorjai et al. (2023) and Kaur et al. (2024) as a plausible source of pyruvate on early Earth."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate carbonylation to pyruvate on greigite-magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite + magnetite mixed mineral assemblage", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, continuous H\u2082 flux"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced to formaldehyde/CO on the mineral surface, followed by C\u2013C bond formation: HCOO\u207b \u2192 CO (bound) + additional CO\u2082/formate \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate via reductive carbonylation. Greigite provides the [FeS] scaffold for C\u2013C coupling analogous to acetyl-CoA synthase.", "reasoning": "The conversion of C1 units (formate, CO\u2082) to C3 pyruvate via reductive carbonylation on iron-sulfur surfaces follows the Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) paradigm. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) specifically discuss this sequence as part of the acetyl-CoA pathway analog operating non-enzymatically on FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces. This provides an alternative route to pyruvate through the formate intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "CO\u2082-rich fluids, alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes carboxylation at the \u03b1-carbon via CO\u2082 insertion, catalyzed by the metal oxide surface of magnetite. This is the reverse of the decarboxylation direction and is driven by the high CO\u2082 partial pressure at hydrothermal conditions. The reaction is: CH\u2083COCOO\u207b + CO\u2082 \u2192 \u207bOOCCH\u2082COCOO\u207b.", "reasoning": "The carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate is the first step of the reductive TCA (rTCA) cycle. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) discuss this as a non-enzymatic analog of pyruvate carboxylase. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated partial rTCA cycle operation on FeS minerals. This reaction is thermodynamically favored under high CO\u2082 pressure at hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082 as reductant, alkaline conditions"}, "mechanism": "The keto group at C2 of oxaloacetate is reduced to a hydroxyl group by H\u2082 on the pyrite surface, yielding malate. This is a straightforward 2e\u207b reduction catalyzed by the FeS\u2082 surface, which activates H\u2082 heterolytically.", "reasoning": "The reduction of oxaloacetate to malate is a well-established step in the reductive TCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated this reaction on Fe\u2070/FeS surfaces under mild conditions. Somorjai et al. (2023) note that ketone-to-alcohol reductions on mineral surfaces are among the most facile prebiotic transformations. This explicit step avoids the lumping criticism of previous attempts."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Thermal dehydration of malate to fumarate", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "moderate-high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface (mild Lewis acid)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Elevated temperature drives dehydration equilibrium"}, "mechanism": "Malate undergoes \u03b1,\u03b2-elimination of water to yield fumarate. The pyrite surface acts as a mild Lewis acid catalyst, stabilizing the transition state for dehydration. This is a thermodynamically straightforward reaction at elevated temperatures.", "reasoning": "The dehydration of malate to fumarate is thermally accessible and has been demonstrated under mild hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2019) observed this reaction as part of the iron-promoted rTCA network. It is one of the simplest steps in the proto-TCA cycle and proceeds readily at temperatures above 370K."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrogenation of fumarate to succinate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082 from serpentinization, alkaline conditions"}, "mechanism": "Fumarate is reduced by H\u2082 across the C=C double bond on the greigite surface, yielding succinate. Greigite activates H\u2082 and transfers hydride to the olefin. This is a classic heterogeneous hydrogenation catalyzed by the iron sulfide surface.", "reasoning": "The reduction of fumarate to succinate is well-supported experimentally. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated this on iron surfaces. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under H\u2082-rich hydrothermal conditions and completes the malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate segment of the reductive TCA cycle. Somorjai et al. (2023) include this in their non-enzymatic proto-metabolism network."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar CO\u2082)", "catalyst": "Fe\u2070 with greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "High CO\u2082 and H\u2082 partial pressures drive the reductive carboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Succinate undergoes oxidative dehydrogenation to form succinyl radical/thioester on the mineral surface, followed by CO\u2082 insertion at the activated carbon to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate. The Fe\u2070 provides reducing equivalents while greigite provides the catalytic [FeS] surface. This is the most thermodynamically demanding step in the proto-rTCA sequence and requires both high CO\u2082 pressure and strong reductants.", "reasoning": "The reductive carboxylation of succinate to \u03b1KG is the most challenging step in the prebiotic rTCA cycle. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) discuss this step explicitly, noting that it requires activation of succinate (possibly via thioester on FeS surfaces) followed by CO\u2082 insertion. Muchowska et al. (2019) achieved partial rTCA operation including this step on Fe\u2070. This reaction is designated as a rate-limiting bottleneck in the network. High CO\u2082 pressure and strong mineral reductants (Fe\u2070) are essential."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1KG to glutamate on Ni-bearing minerals (hydrothermal)", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "Ni-bearing awaruite/Ni-FeS"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Ni-doped greigite or awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a in alkaline vent fluids, H\u2082 saturated, pH ~9-11"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate adsorbs on the Ni-bearing mineral surface. NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b1-keto group to form an imine (Schiff base), which is then reduced by surface-activated H\u2082 to yield glutamate. The Ni centers activate H\u2082 heterolytically while the FeS lattice provides structural support. This is the hydrothermal analog of the Kaur et al. surface reaction.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) demonstrated that Ni catalysts convert \u03b1KG to glutamate via reductive amination with H\u2082 and NH\u2084\u207a at pH 8. In hydrothermal vents, Ni-bearing minerals (awaruite, Ni-doped FeS) are naturally present. Alkaline vent conditions (high H\u2082, NH\u2083, pH 9-11) favor this reductive amination. Somorjai et al. (2023) and the deep research findings note that this step links the proto-TCA cycle to amino acid biosynthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1KG to glutamate on meteoritic Ni (Kaur conditions)", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["meteoritic Ni metal", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K (22\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ni metal powder or meteoritic iron-nickel alloy", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8, 6-150 mM NH\u2084Cl, H\u2082-sparged aqueous solution, ambient temperature"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1KG is converted to glutamate via imine (Schiff base) formation with NH\u2083 at the \u03b1-keto group, followed by H\u2082 reduction on Ni surface. The Ni(0) surface activates H\u2082 and mediates imine hydrogenation under remarkably mild conditions (room temperature, pH 8).", "reasoning": "This is directly from Kaur et al. (2024, Chem): 'H\u2082 and NH\u2084\u207a reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids... Ni at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl converts biological ketoacids including \u03b1KG into the corresponding amino acids in good yields.' This is the best-supported single step for glutamate formation in the network. Meteoritic Ni provides a plausible source of the catalyst on early Earth surface environments."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "UV-photoredox reductive amination of \u03b1KG on TiO\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase photocatalyst)", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 400 nm, no ozone shield), shallow pool, NH\u2083 in solution"}, "mechanism": "UV light excites TiO\u2082 to generate electron-hole pairs. The photoexcited electron reduces the imine intermediate (formed from \u03b1KG + NH\u2083) to glutamate, while the hole oxidizes H\u2082O or H\u2082S. This provides an alternative reductive driving force to H\u2082/metal for the reductive amination.", "reasoning": "TiO\u2082 photocatalysis is well-established for driving organic redox reactions under UV. On the early Earth, intense UV radiation (no ozone layer) could drive photoreductions on mineral surfaces. While no specific experiment has demonstrated UV-driven \u03b1KG\u2192glutamate on TiO\u2082, White et al. have shown UV-driven reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS\u2082 surfaces to yield amino acids. The deep research notes that 'UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures likewise produces complex amino-acid mixtures' (Ring et al. 1972). This route provides a third entry point to glutamate independent of Ni catalysis."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Phosphoryl activation of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl by trimetaphosphate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": false, "other": "Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool; dry phase concentrates reactants and drives condensation; montmorillonite adsorbs glutamate and templates the reaction"}, "mechanism": "During the drying phase, glutamate and trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) are concentrated on the montmorillonite clay surface. The \u03b3-carboxyl of glutamate attacks the electrophilic P center of trimetaphosphate, forming \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate and releasing pyrophosphate. The clay surface orients the glutamate molecule and lowers the activation barrier through Lewis acid catalysis. This is the prebiotic analog of the \u03b3-glutamyl kinase reaction.", "reasoning": "Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) is a well-established prebiotic phosphorylating agent that activates carboxyl groups under dry-down conditions. Guo et al. (2024, Palaeogeogr.) demonstrated that P\u2083m and montmorillonite together drive condensation reactions (specifically amide/peptide bond formation from amino acids including proline derivatives) under wet-dry cycling. The selectivity for the \u03b3-carboxyl over the \u03b1-carboxyl is rationalized by: (1) the \u03b1-carboxyl bears the adjacent NH\u2082 group which creates steric/electronic hindrance, and (2) the \u03b3-carboxyl is more nucleophilic and accessible when glutamate is adsorbed on montmorillonite via its \u03b1-amino group (Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023, Life). This addresses the critical bottleneck identified in previous attempts by providing a chemically specific activation mechanism."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reduction of \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate to glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde on Ni", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["meteoritic Ni metal", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ni metal (meteoritic)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Rewetting phase of wet-dry cycle; H\u2082 in solution; pH ~7-8; phosphate is released as inorganic Pi"}, "mechanism": "Upon rewetting, the \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate dissolves and contacts Ni metal surfaces. The activated acyl phosphate is readily reduced by Ni-activated H\u2082: the phosphate is displaced as a leaving group, and the resulting acyl intermediate is reduced to the aldehyde (semialdehyde). This is chemically analogous to the reduction of acyl phosphates by NaBH\u2084 in organic chemistry, but here H\u2082/Ni provides the hydride.", "reasoning": "Acyl phosphates are much more reactive toward reduction than free carboxylates\u2014this is precisely why biology uses ATP activation before reduction (\u03b3-glutamyl kinase \u2192 \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase). In the prebiotic analog, Ni-activated H\u2082 (Kaur et al. 2024) provides the hydride equivalent. The key insight is that the phosphoryl activation step (rxn_012) converts the thermodynamically difficult carboxylate\u2192aldehyde reduction into a feasible acyl phosphate\u2192aldehyde reduction. This two-step sequence (phosphorylation under dry conditions \u2192 reduction under wet conditions) leverages the wet-dry cycling that Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated for related prebiotic condensation chemistry. This is the most speculative step in the network but is mechanistically justified by analogy to known acyl phosphate chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Thioester-mediated reduction of glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl on FeS", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS\u2082 with surface -SH groups", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082S-rich hydrothermal fluid, pH ~7-9; surface thiol groups on FeS activate the carboxyl"}, "mechanism": "In H\u2082S-rich hydrothermal fluids, the \u03b3-carboxyl of glutamate reacts with surface thiol groups on FeS (mackinawite) to form a surface-bound thioester (glutamyl-S-Fe). This thioester is significantly more electrophilic than the free carboxylate and is reduced by H\u2082 (activated on the same FeS surface) to yield glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde, releasing the thiol. The FeS surface thus acts as both activator and reductant.", "reasoning": "Thioester activation is a cornerstone of the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988; Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). FeS surfaces bear reactive thiol (-SH) groups that form thioesters with carboxylic acids, activating them for reduction. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) specifically note that the glutamate\u2192GS-Ald conversion can occur 'non-enzymatically' and that FeS catalysts are the most likely candidates. The thioester route provides a hydrothermal alternative to the surface phosphoryl activation route (rxn_012/rxn_013), ensuring that the critical bottleneck has two independent solutions operating in different environments."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GS-Ald to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Spontaneous at physiological pH; no catalyst required; rapid intramolecular Schiff base formation"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-amino group of glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde attacks the \u03b3-aldehyde intramolecularly to form a cyclic Schiff base (imine), yielding \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) with loss of water. This 5-exo-trig cyclization is thermodynamically and kinetically favorable (Baldwin's rules), and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous solution at near-neutral pH.", "reasoning": "This spontaneous cyclization is well-established in biochemistry and is considered one of the most reliable steps in the pathway. Somorjai et al. (2023, Phil. Trans.) explicitly state that glutamate semialdehyde 'spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate' non-enzymatically. The intramolecular nature of the reaction makes it kinetically favorable even at low concentrations. This is the step where the linear C5 chain becomes the pyrrolidine ring characteristic of proline."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Reduction of P5C to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "meteoritic Ni metal"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-370K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Ni or FeS surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082 as terminal reductant; pH ~7-9; could occur in either hydrothermal or surface pool environments"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by H\u2082 on Ni or FeS surfaces to yield the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. This is a straightforward imine hydrogenation: the metal surface activates H\u2082 and delivers hydride to the electrophilic C=N carbon. The product is racemic DL-proline, as the reduction is not stereoselective on achiral mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated that Ni surfaces activate H\u2082 for imine reduction under mild conditions. The reduction of P5C to proline is the biological final step catalyzed by P5C reductase (NADPH-dependent), and the prebiotic analog uses H\u2082/metal. Ring et al. (1972) detected proline in Miller-Urey spark discharge products, confirming that proline can form abiotically. The product is racemic; L-enrichment could arise from preferential adsorption of L-proline on chiral mineral faces, as investigated by Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. (2023, Life) who studied proline-mineral surface interactions."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full hydrothermal proto-rTCA to proline via Ni reductive amination and phosphoryl activation", "description": "Complete hydrothermal\u2192surface\u2192biochemical relay: CO\u2082 is reduced to formate, then to pyruvate, through the full proto-rTCA cycle (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate\u2192\u03b1KG), reductive amination to glutamate on Ni (surface, Kaur conditions), phosphoryl activation and reduction of \u03b3-carboxyl, spontaneous cyclization, and final reduction.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Direct pyruvate route with Ni surface reductive amination and phosphoryl activation", "description": "Bypasses formate by using direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate on Fe\u2070 (Varma), then full proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, surface Ni reductive amination (Kaur), and phosphoryl activation route to GS-Ald.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Full hydrothermal proto-rTCA with hydrothermal thioester route to GS-Ald", "description": "Entirely hydrothermal carbon fixation and proto-TCA to \u03b1KG, hydrothermal Ni reductive amination to glutamate, then thioester-mediated \u03b3-carboxyl reduction on FeS to GS-Ald. Spontaneous cyclization and reduction complete the pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Direct pyruvate with hydrothermal thioester route", "description": "Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate on Fe\u2070, proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, hydrothermal Ni-FeS reductive amination, thioester activation on FeS for GS-Ald formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "UV-photoredox glutamate route with phosphoryl activation", "description": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation through formate to pyruvate and proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, then UV-driven reductive amination on TiO\u2082 at the surface to make glutamate. Phosphoryl activation under wet-dry cycling yields GS-Ald.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Direct pyruvate with UV-photoredox and phosphoryl activation", "description": "Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate on Fe\u2070, proto-rTCA, UV-driven glutamate formation on TiO\u2082, phosphoryl activation for \u03b3-carboxyl reduction.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "UV-photoredox glutamate with hydrothermal thioester route", "description": "Formate pathway to pyruvate, proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, UV photoredox for glutamate, then transport back to hydrothermal environment for thioester-mediated GS-Ald formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Direct pyruvate with UV-photoredox and thioester route", "description": "Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate, proto-rTCA, UV-driven glutamate, thioester-mediated \u03b3-carboxyl reduction. Combines the most direct carbon fixation with photochemical amination and hydrothermal activation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Minimal hydrothermal-only pathway (direct pyruvate + hydrothermal amination + thioester)", "description": "The most parsimonious pathway operating primarily within hydrothermal environments. Direct CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate, proto-rTCA to \u03b1KG, hydrothermal Ni-FeS reductive amination, thioester activation for GS-Ald, spontaneous cyclization, and reduction. Only the final cyclization/reduction steps are 'Biochemical.'", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Maximum surface involvement pathway (Kaur amination + phosphoryl activation + surface reduction)", "description": "The pathway that maximizes surface environment participation. Hydrothermal carbon fixation provides \u03b1KG, then surface Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (Kaur et al. 2024), montmorillonite-catalyzed phosphoryl activation under wet-dry cycling, Ni-catalyzed reduction of acyl phosphate, and final assembly. Demonstrates the full Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental relay.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "description": "Pyruvate: convergence of two CO\u2082 fixation routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate: product of proto-rTCA, feeds three independent reductive amination routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Glutamate: convergence of three amination routes, feeds two \u03b3-carboxyl activation routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_014"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde: convergence of phosphoryl activation and thioester activation routes; gateway to ring closure", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "outgo